{"title_page": "Frances Fitzgerald Elmes", "text_new": "'''Frances Fitzgerald Elmes''' (23 April 1867 \u2013 1919) was a British-Australian feminist writer and columnist based in Melbourne and London.<ref name=austlit>[https://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/A26233 \"Frances Fitzgerald\"], ''AustLit'', University of Queensland.</ref><ref name=Morton2011>Peter Morton, ''Lusting for London: Australian Expatriate Writers at the Hub of Empire, 1870\u20131950'', Palgrave MacMillan, 2011, 84\u201385, 255, note 27.</ref><ref>Laura Olcelli, ''Questions of Authority: Italian and Australian Travel Narratives of the Long Nineteenth Century'', New York and Oxford: Routledge, 2017, 159\u2013160.</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Somerset]], England, Elmes emigrated to Australia with her family and was raised in [[Berwick, Victoria]], where her father was a medical practitioner. She became a journalist and wrote for ''[[The Australasian]]'', ''[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]]'' and, after returning to England in 1905, the ''British Australasian''. Her columns, short stories, two books and a play appeared under a variety of pen names, including F. F. Elmes, Frances Fitzgerald, F.&nbsp;F., and Frances Fitzgerald Fawkner.<ref name=Morton2011/>\n\nIn London, Elmes established a relationship with the ''British Australasian''{{'}}s editor, [[Charles Henry Chomley]] (who was married to her close friend Ethel Chomley), during which she is reported to have had two children, a son in 1906 and a daughter in 1908. The relationship was apparently accepted by Chomley's wife and mother.<ref name=Niall2007p150>[[Brenda Niall]], ''The Boyds'', Melbourne: Melbourne University Publishing, 2007, 150.</ref><ref>Brenda Niall, ''Martin Boyd: A Life'', Carlton, Victoria: Melbourne University Press, 1990 [1988], 74\u201376.</ref>\n\nElmes died in London in 1919 during the [[Spanish flu|Spanish flu epidemic]]. After her death, her children were brought up by their father and his wife.<ref name=Niall2007p150/>\n\n==Selected works==\n*Fitzgerald, Frances. ''The New Woman'', a play, performed but not published, 1895.<ref name=austlit/>\n*Elmes, F. F. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=znKFNAAACAAJ The Melbourne Cookery Book]: compiled especially with the view of assisting the housewife in the cottage and villa home who must carefully study ways and means''. Melbourne: Fraser and Jenkinson, 1906. {{oclc|221287128}}\n*Elmes, F. F. [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/10666643?searchTerm=F.%20F.%20Elmes&searchLimits= \"Fashions in Whims: A London Sketch\"], ''The Argus'', 29 February 1908, 6.\n*F.&nbsp;F. [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/154958665 \"The 'Tail' of a Fish\"], ''The Age'', 24 April 1915, 18.\n*Fitzgerald, Frances. ''The Children at Kangaroo Creek'', London: ''British Australasian'', 1916. {{oclc|560859564}}\n*Fitzgerald, Frances. \"The Woman Pays\", ''British Australasian'', 16 August 1917, 31.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[https://trove.nla.gov.au/list?id=120739 \"List: Frances Fitzgerald Elmes\"]. ''Trove''. National Library of Australia.\n*Maria De Jong; Rosalind David, ''Two Remarkable Women: Frances Fitzgerald Fawkner and Sara 'Sally' Rainforth'', Auckland, New Zealand: Remember the Days, 2013. {{isbn|9780473257064}} {{oclc|0473257068}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elmes, Frances}}\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:1919 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian women]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian women]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century writers]]\n\n{{Australia-journalist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Frances Fitzgerald Elmes''' (23 April 1867 \u2013 1919) was a British-Australian feminist writer and columnist based in Melbourne and London.<ref name=austlit>[https://www.austlit.edu.au/austlit/page/A26233 \"Frances Fitzgerald\"], ''AustLit'', University of Queensland.</ref><ref name=Morton2011>Peter Morton, ''Lusting for London: Australian Expatriate Writers at the Hub of Empire, 1870\u20131950'', Palgrave MacMillan, 2011, 84\u201385, 255, note 27.</ref><ref>Laura Olcelli, ''Questions of Authority: Italian and Australian Travel Narratives of the Long Nineteenth Century'', New York and Oxford: Routledge, 2017, 159\u2013160.</ref>\n\nBorn in [[Somerset]], England, Elmes emigrated to Australia with her family and was raised in [[Berwick, Victoria]], where her father was a medical practitioner. She became a journalist and wrote for ''[[The Australasian]]'', ''[[The Argus (Melbourne)|The Argus]]'' and, after returning to England in 1905, the ''British Australasian''. Her columns, short stories, two books and a play appeared under a variety of pen names, including F. F. Elmes, Frances Fitzgerald, F.&nbsp;F., and Frances Fitzgerald Fawkner.<ref name=Morton2011/>\n\nIn London, Elmes established a relationship with the ''British Australasian''{{'}}s editor, [[Charles Henry Chomley]] (who was married to her close friend Ethel Chomley), during which she is reported to have had two children, a son in 1906 and a daughter in 1908. The relationship was apparently accepted by Chomley's wife and mother.<ref name=Niall2007p150>[[Brenda Niall]], ''The Boyds'', Melbourne: Melbourne University Publishing, 2007, 150.</ref><ref>Brenda Niall, ''Martin Boyd: A Life'', Carlton, Victoria: Melbourne University Press, 1990 [1988], 74\u201376.</ref>\n\nElmes died in London in 1919 during the [[Spanish flu|Spanish flu epidemic]]. After her death, her children were brought up by their father and his wife.<ref name=Niall2007p150/>\n\n==Selected works==\n*Fitzgerald, Frances. ''The New Woman'', a play, performed but not published, 1895.<ref name=austlit/>\n*Elmes, F. F. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=znKFNAAACAAJ The Melbourne Cookery Book]: compiled especially with the view of assisting the housewife in the cottage and villa home who must carefully study ways and means''. Melbourne: Fraser and Jenkinson, 1906. {{oclc|221287128}}\n*Elmes, F. F. [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/10666643?searchTerm=F.%20F.%20Elmes&searchLimits= \"Fashions in Whims: A London Sketch\"], ''The Argus'', 29 February 1908, 6.\n*F.&nbsp;F. [https://trove.nla.gov.au/newspaper/article/154958665 \"The 'Tail' of a Fish\"], ''The Age'', 24 April 1915, 18.\n*Fitzgerald, Frances. ''The Children at Kangaroo Creek'', London: ''British Australasian'', 1916. {{oclc|560859564}}\n*Fitzgerald, Frances. \"The Woman Pays\", ''British Australasian'', 16 August 1917, 31.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[https://trove.nla.gov.au/list?id=120739 \"List: Frances Fitzgerald Elmes\"]. ''Trove''. National Library of Australia.\n*Maria De Jong; Rosalind David, ''Two Remarkable Women: Frances Fitzgerald Fawkner and Sara 'Sally' Rainforth'', Auckland, New Zealand: Remember the Days, 2013. {{isbn|9780473257064}} {{oclc|0473257068}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elmes, Frances}}\n[[Category:1863 births]]\n[[Category:1919 deaths]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian journalists]]\n[[Category:19th-century Australian women]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian women]]\n[[Category:20th-century Australian writers]]\n[[Category:19th-century writers]]\n\n\n{{Australia-journalist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Chris.sherlock", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frances_Fitzgerald_Elmes"}
{"title_page": "Brian Ortega", "text_new": "{{short description|American mixed martial artist}}\n{{Infobox martial artist\n| name            = Brian Ortega\n| nickname        = T-City\n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| alt             =\n| caption         =\n| birth_name      = Brian Martin Ortega\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|1991|2|21}}\n| birth_place     = [[Los Angeles, California]], United States\n| death_date      = \n| death_place     =\n| death_cause     =\n| residence       =\n| nationality     = [[Americans|American]]\n| ethnicity       =\n| height          = 5 ft 8 in <!-- as per Sherdog -https://www.sherdog.com/fighter/Brian-Ortega-65310-->\n| weight          = 146 lb\n| weight_class    = [[Featherweight (MMA)|Featherweight]]<br>[[Lightweight (MMA)|Lightweight]]\n| reach           = 69 in<ref name=\"bo profile\">{{cite web|url=http://ufc.com/fighter/Brian-Ortega |title=Brian Ortega UFC Profile |publisher=UFC.com|accessdate=January 14, 2017}}</ref>\n| stance          = \n| style           = [[Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu]]\n| fighting_out_of = [[Torrance, California]], United States\n| team            = Black Belt Surfing<br>[[Black House (MMA)|Black House MMA]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.blackhousemma.com/fighters/brian-ortega# |title=Black House MMA Brian Ortega Profile |access-date=2012-02-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120216053730/http://www.blackhousemma.com/fighters/brian-ortega# |archive-date=2012-02-16 |url-status=dead }}</ref><br>Gracie Jiu-Jitsu Academy\n| rank            = Black belt in [[Brazilian Jiu-Jitsu]] <small>under [[Rener Gracie]]</small><ref name=BJJ>{{cite web |url=http://www.gracieacademy.com/belt_holders_centers.asp |title=Certified Gracies Jiu-Jitsu Belt Holders |publisher=gracieacademy.com |accessdate=December 11, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Q-7cf48x2oY& |title=Brian Ortega receives 1st degree black belt in BJJ |accessdate=2019-12-27}}</ref>\n| years_active    = 2010\u2013present\n| mma_kowin       = 3\n| mma_subwin      = 7\n| mma_decwin      = 4\n| mma_koloss      = 1\n| mma_subloss     = \n| mma_decloss     = \n| mma_draw        =\n| mma_nc          = 1\n| url             =\n| sherdog         = 65310\n| footnotes       =\n| updated         =\n}}\n\n'''Brian Martin Ortega'''<ref>http://boxing.nv.gov/uploadedFiles/boxingnvgov/content/results/2016_Results/01-02-16MMA.pdf</ref> (born February 21, 1991) is an [[United States|American]] [[Mixed martial arts|mixed martial artist]] in the [[Featherweight (MMA)|featherweight]] division of the [[Ultimate Fighting Championship]] (UFC). A professional since 2010, he has also competed for the [[Resurrection Fighting Alliance|RFA]], where he was the Featherweight Champion. As of February 25, 2019, he is #2 in the [[List of current UFC fighters#Rankings|UFC featherweight rankings]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://uk.ufc.com/rankings|title=Fighter Rankings {{!}} UFC \u00ae|website=UFC|language=en|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref>.\n\n== Background ==\nOrtega was born in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]]; he's of [[Mexicans|Mexican]] descent and possesses dual nationality, as both his parents are from [[Hermosillo]], [[Sonora]], [[Mexico]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Owens |first1=Michael |title=Brian Ortega: \"Let them choose how they lose.\" |url=https://www.fightersonlymag.com/interviews/brian-ortega-let-choose-lose/ |accessdate=2018-06-15 |agency=Fighters Only |publisher=fightersonlymag.com |date=2017-07-26}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Brian Ortega Awarded \"Hispanic Athlete of the Year\" from Inca Kola & NY Business Latino |url=http://fightnetwork.com/news/6642903:brian-ortega-awarded-hispanic-athlete-of-the-year-from-inca-kola-ny-business-latino/ |accessdate=2018-06-15 |agency=Fight Network |publisher=fightnetwork.com |date=2018-02-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615192232/http://fightnetwork.com/news/6642903:brian-ortega-awarded-hispanic-athlete-of-the-year-from-inca-kola-ny-business-latino/ |archive-date=2018-06-15 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Del Campo |first1=Rodrigo |title=BRIAN ORTEGA: UNA ESTRELLA A PUNTO DE ESTALLAR |url=http://www.ufc.com/news/ufc-199-brian-ortega-pelea?id= |accessdate=2018-06-15 |agency=Ultimate Fighting Championship |publisher=ufc.com |date=2016-05-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Flores |first1=Edgar |title='SOY UN MEXICANO ORGULLOSO DE LUCHAR': BRIAN ORTEGA |url=http://www.record.com.mx/extremo/soy-un-mexicano-orgulloso-de-luchar-brian-ortega |accessdate=2018-06-15 |agency=Record |publisher=record.com.mx |date=2016-06-02}}</ref><ref name=\"background1\">{{cite news |title=BRIAN \"T-CITY\" ORTEGA AWARDED \"HISPANIC ATHLETE OF THE YEAR\" |url=https://lfafighting.com/brian-t-city-ortega-awarded-hispanic-athlete-of-the-year/ |accessdate=2018-06-15 |agency=Legacy Fighting Alliance |publisher=lfafighting.com |date=2018-02-06}}</ref> He grew up in section 8 housing project of [[San Pedro, Los Angeles|San Pedro]], California.<ref name=\"break\">{{Citation|last=GracieBreakdown|title=The Brian Ortega Story (Fox Sports 1)|date=2017-09-14|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=YK1Qkg07qls|accessdate=2017-09-16}}</ref> Brian started learning martial arts when he was 5 years old at Al Martinez Muay Thai Kickboxing in Wilmington, CA. <ref name=\"background1\"/> When he turned 13, he began training [[Brazilian Jiu Jitsu|Brazilian jiu-jitsu]] at the Gracie Jiu-Jitsu Academy under [[Rorion Gracie]], and his sons Ryron, [[Rener Gracie|Rener]], and [[Ralek Gracie]] in [[Torrance, California]].<ref name=BJJ /><ref name=\"background1\"/>\n\n== Mixed martial arts career ==\n\n===Early career===\nWhen Ortega was 17, he met boxing coach James Luhrsen, who took him in and trained him in striking skills.<ref name=\"break\"/> Ortega began his career competing for regional promotions exclusively in [[Southern California]].<ref>[http://www.sherdog.com/fighter/Brian-Ortega-65310 Sherdog >> Fighter Profile >> Brian Ortega] URL accessed on October 11, 2011.</ref> He won his first pro-MMA championship against Carlos Garces in a five-round bout via unanimous decision, becoming the Respect In The Cage featherweight champion.<ref name=\"Brian\">[http://www.respectinthecage.com/ Respect in the Cage Featured Fighters]. URL accessed on October 11, 2011.</ref>\n\nOrtega went on to compile an undefeated record of 8-0 before signing with the UFC in April 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bloodyelbow.com/2014/4/8/5593942/welcome-to-the-ufc-brian-ortega-vs-diego-brandao-tuf-brazil-3-finale-mma-news|title=Welcome to the UFC Brian Ortega|publisher=bloodyelbow.com|author=Zane Simon|date=2014-04-08|accessdate=2014-04-08}}</ref> He credited his success to support and love from James Luhrsen and Rener Gracie.<ref>{{Citation|last=FloGrappling|title=Eddie Bravo: Building An Empire (EP 1)|date=2017-07-05|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=4tQle5yHUYg|accessdate=2017-09-16}}</ref>\n\n===Ultimate Fighting Championship===\nOrtega was expected to make his promotional debut against [[Diego Brand\u00e3o]] on May 31, 2014, at [[The Ultimate Fighter: Brazil 3#The Ultimate Fighter Brazil 3 Finale: Miocic vs. Maldonado|The Ultimate Fighter Brazil 3 Finale]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportv.globo.com/site/combate/noticia/2014/04/diego-brandao-enfrenta-o-estreante-brian-ortega-no-tuf-brasil-3-finale.html|title=Diego Brand\u00e3o enfrenta o estreante Brian Ortega no TUF Brasil 3 Finale (Brazilian Portuguese)|publisher=sportv.globo.com|author=Ivan Raupp|accessdate=2014-04-08|date=2014-04-08}}</ref> However, Brandao pulled out of the bout in the days leading up to the event citing an injury. Due to the late nature of the change, officials did not try to find a replacement and Ortega was pulled from the card as well.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2014/5/19/5732660/diego-brandao-injured-tuf-brazil-3-finale-bout-with-brian-ortega|title=Diego Brandao injured, TUF: Brazil 3 Finale bout with Brian Ortega scratched |publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Guilherme Cruz|date=2014-05-19|accessdate=2013-05-19}}</ref>\n\nOrtega eventually made his debut on July 26, 2014, at [[UFC on Fox 12]] against [[Mike De La Torre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fightline.com/ufc-fox-12-picks-brian-ortega-mike-de-la-torre/|title=UFC on FOX 12 picks up Brian Ortega-Mike De La Torre |publisher=fightline.com |author=Dana Becker|date=2014-06-12|accessdate=2013-06-12}}</ref> Originally, a first round submission (rear-naked choke) win for Ortega, the result was changed to \"[[No contest (combat sports)|No Contest]]\" after Ortega tested positive for [[drostanolone]] during a post fight screening. Subsequently, Ortega was fined $2,500 and suspended for nine months.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/ExRFA-Champ-Brian-Ortega-Tests-Positive-for-Anabolic-Steroids-Following-UFC-on-Fox-12-72245|title=Ex-RFA Champ Brian Ortega tests positive for anabolic steroids following UFC on Fox 12|publisher=sherdog.com |author=C.J. Tuttle|date=August 22, 2014|accessdate=August 22, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Brian-Ortega-Apologizes-for-Failed-Drug-Test-at-UFC-on-Fox-12-72371|title=Brian Ortega apologizes for failed drug test at UFC on Fox 12|publisher=sherdog.com|author=Tristen Critchfield|date=August 23, 2014|accessdate=August 23, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOrtega faced [[Thiago Tavares]] on June 6, 2015, at [[UFC Fight Night 68]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2015/5/5/8557551/thiago-tavares-announces-fight-with-brian-ortega-at-ufc-fight-night-68|title=Thiago Tavares announces fight with Brian Ortega at UFC Fight Night 68|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Guilherme Cruz|date=May 5, 2015|accessdate=May 5, 2015}}</ref> He won the back-and-forth fight via TKO in the third round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com/ufc/story/ufc-brian-ortega-tko-s-thiago-tavares-in-crowd-pleasing-battle-060615|title=Brian Ortega TKO's Thiago Tavares in crowd pleasing battle|publisher=foxsports.com|author=Damon Martin|date=2015-06-06|accessdate=2015-06-06}}</ref> Both participants were awarded ''Fight of the Night'' honors.<ref name=\"Matt Erickson\">{{cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2015/06/ufc-fight-night-68-bonuses-dustin-poirier-gets-50000-in-front-of-home-fans|title=UFC Fight Night 68 bonuses: Dustin Poirier gets $50,000 in front of home fans|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Matt Erickson|date=2015-06-07|accessdate=2015-06-07}}</ref>\n\nOrtega faced [[Diego Brand\u00e3o]], who is a second-degree black belt in Brazilian jiu-jitsu, on January 2, 2016, at [[UFC 195]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2015/11/brian-ortega-vs-diego-brandao-added-to-ufc-195-in-las-vegas|title=Brian Ortega vs. Diego Brandao added to UFC 195 in Las Vegas|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=2015-11-14|accessdate=2015-11-14}}</ref> After being down against Diego's striking for the first two rounds, Ortega rallied and won via triangle choke in the third round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2016/01/ufc-195-results-brian-ortegas-sick-jiu-jitsu-leads-to-triangle-choke-of-diego-brandao|title=UFC 195 results: Brian Ortega's sick jiu-jitsu leads to triangle choke of Diego Brandao|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Steven Marrocoo|date=2016-01-02|accessdate=2016-01-02}}</ref>\n\nAt [[UFC 199]] on June 4, 2016, Ortega defeated [[Clay Guida]] by KO in the third round. After winning the first round, Guida won the second round and looked to have the third won until Ortega rallied and won via a flying knee near the end of the round.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mmafighting.com/2016/6/4/11860100/ufc-199-results-brian-ortega-steals-win-from-clay-guida-with-last|title=UFC 199 results: Brian Ortega steals win from Clay Guida with last-minute knockout|publisher=mmafighting.com|author=Dave Doley|date=2016-06-04|accessdate=2016-06-05}}</ref>\n\nOrtega was expected to face [[Hacran Dias]] on October 1, 2016, at [[UFC Fight Night 96]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2016/08/report-hacran-dias-vs-brian-ortega-added-to-ufc-fight-night-96-in-portland|title=Hacran Dias vs. Brian Ortega added to UFC Fight Night 96 in Portland |publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=2016-08-03|accessdate=2016-08-03}}</ref> However, Ortega pulled out of the fight in early September and was replaced by [[Andre Fili]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oregonlive.com/sports/index.ssf/2016/09/ufc_announces_update_to_portla.html|title=Brian Ortega withdraws from UFC Fight Night 96 in Portland|publisher=oregonlive.com|author=Staff|date=2016-09-12|accessdate=2016-09-12}}</ref>\n\nOrtega next faced [[Renato Moicano]] on July 29, 2017, at [[UFC 214]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailynews.com/sports/20170526/brian-ortega-returns-at-ufc-214-vs-renato-moicano|title=Brian Ortega returns at UFC 214 vs. Renato Moicano |publisher=dailynews.com|author=Brian Martin|date=2017-05-26|accessdate=2017-05-26}}</ref> He won the back and forth fight via submission in the third round with a guillotine choke,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/07/ufc-214-results-brian-ortega-record-fourth-straight-win-by-third-round-finish|title=UFC 214 results: Brian Ortega earns record 4th straight win by 3rd-round finish vs. Renato Moicano|date=2017-07-30|work=MMAjunkie|access-date=2017-07-31|language=en-US}}</ref> while both fighters were awarded [[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Fight of the Night]] bonus.<ref name=\"Bloody Elbow\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloodyelbow.com/2017/7/30/16064504/ufc-214-post-fight-bonuses-jon-jones-brian-ortega-among-50k-winners|title=UFC 214 bonuses: Jones, Ortega among $50K winners|work=Bloody Elbow|access-date=2017-07-31}}</ref>\n\nOrtega faced [[Cub Swanson]] on December 9, 2017, at [[UFC Fight Night 123]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/10/cub-swanson-brian-ortega-ufc-fight-night-113-fresno-main-event|title=Cub Swanson says he's headlining UFC Fight Night 123 against Brian Ortega|publisher=mmajunkie.com|author=Staff|date=2017-10-02|accessdate=2017-10-02}}</ref> He was victorious in the fight, winning in the second round by guillotine choke submission. The finish put Ortega's streak at five straight fights won with a finish, which at the time was the second longest current win streak in the UFC featherweight division behind the champion, [[Max Holloway]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sherdog.com/news/articles/UFC-Fight-Night-123-By-the-Numbers-130143|publisher=Sherdog|title=UFC Fight Night 123 By the Numbers|date=December 10, 2017}}</ref> The win also earned him the Fight of the Night and Performance of the Night honors.<ref name=\"Staff\">{{citeweb|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2017/12/ufc-fight-night-123-bonuses-brian-ortegas-amazing-performance-doubles-up-for-100000|title=UFC Fight Night 123 bonuses: Brian Ortega's amazing performance doubles up for $100,000|author=Staff|publisher=MMAJunkie.com|date=2017-12-10|accessdate=2017-12-10}}</ref>\n\nOrtega faced [[Frankie Edgar]] on March 3, 2018, at [[UFC 222]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/2/7/16968430/cris-cyborg-vs-yana-kunitskaya-frankie-edgar-vs-brian-ortega-scheduled-for-ufc-222|title=Cris Cyborg vs. Yana Kunitskaya, Frankie Edgar vs. Brian Ortega scheduled for UFC 222|work=MMA Fighting|access-date=2018-02-08}}</ref> He won the fight via knockout in the first round. In doing so, he became the first man to ever finish Edgar in MMA.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.mmanews.com/brian-ortega-pulls-off-shocking-knockout-win-edgar-secure-title-shot/|title=Brian Ortega Pulls Off Shocking Knockout Win Over Edgar To Secure Title Shot|work=MMA News}}</ref> This win earned him the [[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Performance of the Night]] bonus.<ref name=\"MMAjunkie\">{{Cite news|url=http://mmajunkie.com/2018/03/ufc-222-bonuses-brian-ortega-alexander-hernandez-sean-omalley-andre-soukhamthath-mma|title=UFC 222 bonuses: Brian Ortega, Alexander Hernandez easy choices for $50,000|date=2018-03-04|work=MMAjunkie|access-date=2018-03-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nOrtega was scheduled to face [[Max Holloway]] for the [[UFC Featherweight Champion]]ship on July 7, 2018, at [[UFC 226]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/mma/max-holloway-defend-title-vs-brian-ortega-ufc-226/|title=Max Holloway to defend title vs. Brian Ortega at UFC 226 - Sportsnet.ca|work=Sportsnet.ca|access-date=2018-04-21|language=en-US}}</ref> However, on July 4, Holloway was pulled from the fight due to \"concussion like symptoms\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2018/07/max-holloway-withdraws-ufc-226-concussion-like-symptom|title=Max Holloway out of UFC 226, hospitalized with concussion-like symptoms|date=2018-07-05|work=MMAjunkie|access-date=2018-07-05|language=en-US}}</ref> Hence, Ortega scratched from the fight after Holloway's withdrawal.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2018/07/brian-ortega-scratched-ufc-226-max-holloway-withdraws|title=Brian Ortega scratched from UFC 226 after champ Max Holloway withdraws|date=2018-07-05|work=MMAjunkie|access-date=2018-07-12|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nThe fight against [[Max Holloway]] eventually took place on December 8, 2018, in the main event at [[UFC 231]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://cagesidepress.com/2018/08/25/max-holloway-vs-brian-ortega-works-ufc-231/|title=Max Holloway vs. Brian Ortega In The Works for UFC 231|date=2018-08-25|work=Cageside Press|access-date=2018-08-25|language=en-US}}</ref> Ortega lost the fight by doctor stoppage at the end of the fourth round.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2018/12/9/18132662/ufc-231-results-max-holloway-defeats-brian-ortega-in-thrilling-four-round-war|title=UFC 231 results: Max Holloway defeats Brian Ortega in thrilling four-round war|last=Doyle|first=Dave|date=2018-12-09|website=MMA Fighting|access-date=2019-02-25}}</ref> This fight earned him the ''[[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Fight of the Night]]'' award.<ref name=\"mmajunkie.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.com/2018/12/ufc-231-bonuses-max-holloway-gets-two-thiago-marreta-santos|title=UFC 231 bonuses: Max Holloway earns double after dominant title defense|date=2018-12-09|website=MMAjunkie|language=en|access-date=2018-12-09}}</ref>\n\nOrtega was scheduled to face [[Chan Sung Jung]] on December 21, 2019 at [[UFC on ESPN+ 23]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/9/23/20880908/brian-ortega-vs-the-korean-zombie-chan-sung-jung-headlines-ufcs-return-to-south-korea|title=Brian Ortega vs. \u2018The Korean Zombie\u2019 Chan Sung Jung headlines UFC\u2019s return to South Korea|last=Martin|first=Damon|date=2019-09-23|website=MMA Fighting|language=en|access-date=2019-09-24}}</ref>  However, Ortega pulled out of the fight in early December citing a knee injury.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmafighting.com/2019/12/5/20996673/brian-ortega-out-of-ufc-busan-main-event-against-korean-zombie-chan-sung-jung|title=Brian Ortega out of UFC Busan main event against \u2018Korean Zombie\u2019 Chan Sung Jung|author=Damon Martin|website=mmafighting.com|date=2019-12-05|access-date=2019-12-05}}</ref>\n\n==Championships and accomplishments==\n*'''[[Ultimate Fighting Championship]]'''\n**[[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Fight of the Night]] (Four times) {{small|vs. [[Thiago Tavares]], [[Renato Moicano]], [[Cub Swanson]] and [[Max Holloway]]}}<ref name=\"Matt Erickson\"/><ref name=\"Bloody Elbow\"/><ref name=\"Staff\"/><ref name=\"mmajunkie.com\"/>\n**[[List of UFC bonus award recipients|Performance of the Night]] (Two times) {{small|vs. [[Cub Swanson]] and [[Frankie Edgar]]}}<ref name=\"Staff\"/><ref name=\"MMAjunkie\"/>\n*'''[[World MMA Awards]]'''\n**2017 Breakthrough Fighter of the Year\n*'''[[MMAjunkie.com|MMAJunkie.com]]'''\n**2015 June Fight of the Month <small>vs. [[Thiago Tavares]]</small><ref>http://mmajunkie.com/2015/07/mmajunkies-fight-of-the-month-for-june-featherweight-bangers-steal-the-show</ref>\n*'''[[Resurrection Fighting Alliance]]'''\n**RFA Featherweight Champion (one time)\n\n== Controversies ==\n=== UFC 248 Incident ===\n\nOn March 8, 2020, a police report was filed against Ortega for alleged slapping Korean American rapper [[Jay Park]], translator for [[Chan Sung Jung]] (Korean Zombie), at [[UFC 248]] after Jung left to use the washroom.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mmajunkie.usatoday.com/2020/03/korean-zombie-chan-sung-jung-manager-police-report-brian-ortega-slap-ufc-248|title=Chan Sung Jung manager: Police report filed after alleged Brian Ortega slap at UFC 248|date=2020-03-08|website=MMA Junkie|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mmamania.com/2020/3/8/21170277/brian-ortega-thrown-out-of-ufc-248-after-slapping-k-pop-star-and-korean-zombie-translator-jay-park|title=Brian Ortega thrown out of UFC 248 after slapping K-Pop star Jay Park|last=Harkness|first=Ryan|date=2020-03-08|website=MMAmania.com|language=en|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref> Jung posted a statement on social media following the incident saying \"Last night, you sat 10 meters away from me and Jay Park. For two hours nothing happened, so I thought everything was fine. But you fucking attacked Jay Park while I went to the bathroom. Jay Park is not a professional fighter but a musician. You slapped a civilian who merely helped translate [...] Even worse, you were sitting there waiting until I would be absent and attacked Jay Park. It was not a fight like real men would do. What you have done is same as a grown up to beat a child. You should have attacked me. If so, I would have not been upset.You are such a coward for slapping a musician not a fighter.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sherdog.com/news/news/Korean-Zombie-Blasts-Coward-Brian-Ortega-After-UFC-248-Slapping-Incident-171285|title=\u2018Korean Zombie\u2019 Blasts \u2018Coward\u2019 Brian Ortega After UFC 248 Slapping Incident|last=Sherdog.com|website=Sherdog|access-date=2020-03-09}}</ref>\n\n==Mixed martial arts record==\n{{MMArecordbox\n|ko-wins=3\