{"title_page": "ST Kinetics", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = ST Engineering Land Systems\n| logo                = https://www.google.com/search?q=st+kinetics&rlz=1C1CHBD_enSG893SG893&sxsrf=ALeKk0298f1i7X4U4vVo4P7UzyAkpzQGVA:1587459902201&tbm=isch&source=iu&ictx=1&fir=8gbGKWpcZbY6xM%253A%252CDlacC9jFD5pEAM%252C%252Fm%252F0g0gr3&vet=1&usg=AI4_-kRRLEbI65jJ4BbL1gAoI4GBmPP5gA&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjnjcP8lPnoAhUIU30KHcsUCV8Q_B0wDXoECAwQAw#imgrc=8gbGKWpcZbY6xM:\n| type                = [[Subsidiary]] of ST Engineering\n| foundation          = {{start date and age|df=y|1967|01|27}} as the Chartered Industries of Singapore (CIS)\n| key_people          = Dr. Lee Tsien Long, President STELS<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography of Dr LEE Shiang Long, President, Land Systems|url=https://www.stengg.com/media/617909/bio-dr-lee-shiang-long-6-jun-2019.pdf|date=6 June 2019|archive-url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:WB8R6zItcbsJ:https://www.stengg.com/media/617909/bio-dr-lee-shiang-long-6-jun-2019.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| location            = Singapore\n| industry            = [[Arms industry|Defence]]<br/> Commercial Vehicles<br/> Automotive Services\n| products            = [[Ammunition]]<br/> [[Firearm]]s <br/> [[Weapon]]s <br/>Armored vehicles, [[IFV]]/[[Armoured patrol vehicle|APV]]<br/> Vehicle MRO Services <br/> [[Emergency vehicle]]s <br/> [[Truck|Distribution Vehicles]] <br/> [[Heavy Equipment|Construction Equipment]]s <br/> Testing Services\n| revenue             = > S$1.43b (2019)\n| num_employees       = > 7,000 (2013)\n| parent              = [[ST Engineering]]\n| homepage            = [http://www.stengg.com/]\n}}\n\n'''Singapore Technologies Land Systems Ltd (STELS, formerly ST Kinetics)''', in [[Singapore]], is a strategic business area of [[ST Engineering]] and handles land systems and specialty vehicles.\n\nIn 2000, ST Engineering acquired the Chartered Industries of Singapore (CIS) through ST Automotive, a subsidiary of ST Engineering, and the new company was named ST Kinetics. Given the initial charter of CIS to support the local defence requirements, the main defence customer of ST Kinetics remains as the [[Singapore Armed Forces]] (SAF).\n\nBesides manufacturing [[small arms]] and [[munitions]], some of STELS' key military products include the [[SAR 21]] assault rifle, the [[Bionix AFV]], the [[Bronco All Terrain Tracked Carrier]] and the [[Terrex ICV|Terrex APC]]. These weapons and ammunition are often made to U.S. or NATO specifications for export. The company holds a number of subsidiaries overseas, mainly in the U.S., Canada, China and India.\n\nRecent [[acquisitions]] between 2004 and 2009 have seen new construction equipment, specialised bodies and trailers for urban services being brought into ST Kinetics' stable of products, which was previously dominated by military weapons and platforms. Together with the other ST Engineering companies, STELS is part of the Singapore Defence Ecosystem of users, developers and producers in support of the Third Generation SAF.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= [[Jane's Defence Weekly]] |title= Industry Briefing&nbsp;\u2014 Singapore: Defence Ecosystem |access-date= 15 January 2008 |year= 2006 |url= http://www.dso.org.sg/data/JDW_Feb15_Defence_Ecosystem_210220061215.pdf |format= PDF |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070412014859/http://www.dso.org.sg/data/JDW_Feb15_Defence_Ecosystem_210220061215.pdf |archive-date= 12 April 2007 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===1967\u20131986: Rapid growth and expansion===\nCIS was originally incorporated on 27 January 1967, when it started out by producing [[Weapon|ordnance]] for the SAF.<ref name=milestones>{{Cite web |publisher= [[ST Engineering]] |title= Milestones |access-date= 26 December 2007 |year= 2006 |url= http://www.stengg.com/kinetics/historymilestones.aspx |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080118173832/http://www.stengg.com/kinetics/historymilestones.aspx |archive-date= 18 January 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> CIS' first product was the [[5.56\u00d745mm NATO]] round; other CIS products include the license-built [[Colt's Manufacturing Company|Colt]] [[M16 rifle|M16S1]] (equivalent to the M16A1), and locally designed weapons such as the [[Ultimax 100]] SAW, the [[SAR-80]] and the [[SR-88]] assault rifles. Several other companies were formed under CIS over the span of the next 2 decades, with the expansion of the defence business, such as Unicorn International (UI) in 1971, Ordnance & Development Engineering (ODE) in 1973, Singapore Test Services (STS) in 1980 and Chartered Chemicals (CCI) in 1982.\n\nShortly after the formation of CIS, the Defence Minister, Dr [[Goh Keng Swee]], went on to set up several other government-linked defence industries to provide indigenous support for the SAF. One of them was Singapore Automotive Engineering (SAE). SAE was to support automotive-related services for the SAF, and its first immediate task was to service and maintain a fleet of [[Cadillac Gage Commando|V200]] armored vehicles.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= [[National University of Singapore|NUS]] |title= Refer to Year 1970 |url= http://www.tdsi.nus.edu.sg/Downloads/Staff/MB_LPC.html |access-date= 3 January 2008 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20071230234028/http://www.tdsi.nus.edu.sg/Downloads/Staff/MB_LPC.html |archive-date= 30 December 2007 |url-status= live }}</ref> By 1982, amidst a young, thriving Singapore economy and having built up its capability in automotive servicing and standards, SAE saw the potential in the commercial sector and decided to incorporate SAE Inspection Centre for vehicle inspection and servicing. The following year, Singapore Commuters, a taxi service, was formed.\n\n===1987\u20131996: Reformation===\nOn 20 August 1991, SAE was publicly listed on the [[Singapore Stock Exchange]].<ref name= milestones/> In the same year, SAE was renamed Singapore Technologies Automotive (ST Auto). STA Detroit Diesel-Allison was formed to take on the maintenance of the Detroit diesel engines and Allison transmission used in the Bionix as well as to distribute the Detroit Diesel parts in the Asian region.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= ST Engineering |title= Company profile SDDA |url= http://www.stengg.com/aboutus/company_detail.aspx?cypid=5&cyid=23 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080202135436/http://www.stengg.com/aboutus/company_detail.aspx?cypid=5&cyid=23 |archive-date= 2 February 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSingapore Commuters was merged with Singapore Airport Services Ltd (SABS Taxi Ltd) and Singapore Bus Service Taxi Pte Ltd (SBS Taxi Pte Ltd) to form CitiCab in April 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|publisher=CityCab |title=Company Profile |url=http://www.citycab.com.sg/abtus/cc_history.htm |access-date=31 December 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224065919/http://www.citycab.com.sg/abtus/cc_history.htm |archive-date=24 December 2007 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> By 1996, CIS through its various subsidiaries were producing various ordnance for the SAF and for export overseas. Chartered Ammunition Industries (CAI) was producing small, medium and large caliber ammunition, explosives, pyrotechnics and anti-tank weapons. ODE was producing medium to large caliber weapon systems (mortars, medium caliber cannons, FH88, FH2000). Chartered Firearms Industries (CFI) was producing infantry and crew-served weapons, including the SR88A assault rifle, Ultimax 100, 7.62&nbsp;mm GPMG, the 40&nbsp;mm grenade launchers, and the 40/50 Cupola Weapon system. Allied Ordnance of Singapore (AOS) was offering a range of advanced low-level air defence equipment, including the 40&nbsp;mm L70 air defense gun system, and missile and Optronic fire control systems.\n\nFor the automotive business, ST Auto took on the AMX-13 Light Tank upgrading project, and refurbished the M113 APC, Commando V100 and V200 armored vehicles, LARC V amphibious. ST Auto also signed a contract with the SAF to overhaul, maintain and repair its military ground equipment. Singapore Test Services by then was offering specialized tests and inspection services to both military and civilian customers.<ref name= FAS/>\n\n===1997\u2013present: Reinvention===\nIn 1997, ST Auto, together with Singapore Technologies Aerospace Ltd (ST Aerospace), Singapore Technologies Electronics Ltd (ST Electronics), and Singapore Technologies Marine Ltd (ST Marine), were merged to form the present ST Engineering.<ref>{{cite press release |publisher= ST Engineering |title= Joint Announcement&nbsp;\u2014 Singapore Technologies Engineering Companies Amalgamating for Strength |date= 28 August 1997 |url= http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=480 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080202135452/http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=480 |archive-date= 2 February 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn October 1999, ST Engineering acquired CIS at S$78 M.<ref>{{cite press release |publisher= ST Engineering |title= ST Engg Acquires Chartered Industries of Singapore (CIS) |date= 22 October 1999 |url= http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=243 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080202135420/http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=243 |archive-date= 2 February 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> ST Auto and CIS were merged in Feb 2000 to form ST Kinetics.<ref>{{cite press release |title= ST Engg Positions for Land Systems Market |date= 18 February 2000 |url= http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=461 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080202135425/http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=461 |archive-date= 2 February 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The following year, ST Kinetics reorganised itself into 3 divisions, namely Automotive; Munitions and Weapons; and Services, Trading and Others.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Retrospective: Land System, see page 26 | url = http://www.stengg.com/investorelations/pdf/ar2001.pdf | format = PDF | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070226135511/http://www.stengg.com/investorelations/pdf/ar2001.pdf | archive-date = 26 February 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> A series of flagship products were developed by the early 21st century, including the SAR21 assault rifle, the Primus 155mm self-propelled artillery gun, the Pegasus 155&nbsp;mm lightweight howitzer, the Bronco All-Terrain Tracked Carrier and the Terrex 8\u00d78 Armoured Personnel Carrier.\n\nST Kinetics went on to invest in several companies overseas to enhance its engineering capabilities. An example was the acquisition of Silvatech Industries Inc in July 2006, a Canadian company specialising in forestry equipment, and renaming it as Kinetics Drive Solutions (KDS) in August 2006<ref>{{cite press release |publisher= ST Kinetics |date= 4 August 2006 |title= Change of Subsidiary Name |url= http://www.stengg.com/press-centre/press-releases/change-of-subsidiary-name-1 |archive-url= https://archive.is/20130411213412/http://www.stengg.com/press-centre/press-releases/change-of-subsidiary-name-1 |url-status= dead |archive-date= 11 April 2013 }}</ref> to focus on the [[Infinitely Variable Transmission]]s (IVT) that Silvatech had developed for its forestry equipment.\n\n2003 was the year ST Kinetics decided to venture into the new commercial vehicles business to leverage on the engineering and fabrication capabilities it has acquired through the military vehicle projects. That year, ST Kinetics went into an equal-share joint venture with Beijing Heavy Duty Truck Plant (BHDTP) to form the Beijing Zhonghuan Kinetics Heavy Vehicles Co. Ltd (BZK).<ref>{{cite press release |publisher= ST Kinetics |date= 26 March 2004 |title= Beijing JV Company Obtains Regulatory Approvals |url= http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=612 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080202135457/http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=612 |archive-date= 2 February 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, ST Kinetics acquired Specialized Vehicles Corporation in U.S. along with its Hackney and Kidron brands, 2 market leaders in the U.S. beverage truck bodies business.<ref name=press_828>{{cite press release |publisher= ST Kinetics |date= 1 August 2005 |title= ST Engineering Acquires Specialized Vehicles Corporations |url= http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=828 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080202135509/http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=828 |archive-date= 2 February 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> In the same year, ST Kinetics signed a 60\u201340 joint venture with Guiyang City Industrial Investment Holding Corporation (GIIHC) to form Guizhou Jonyang Kinetics Co., Ltd. (GJK) that manufactures excavators,<ref name= press_828/> and set up STAR Guangzhou and STAR Hangzhou.\n\nIn June 2006, ST Kinetics wholly acquired Leeboy through ST Engineering's U.S. subsidiary, VT Systems. Leeboy is a U.S. industry leader in commercial class asphalt pavers.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= Leeboy |title= Company Profile |url= http://www.leeboy.com/showcontent.aspx?id=121 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080201173216/http://www.leeboy.com/showcontent.aspx?id=121 |archive-date= 1 February 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, ST Kinetics reorganised itself into 2 business groups. The Defence Business Group handles all military business and the Commercial Business Group manages the commercial businesses.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= ST Kinetics |title= ST Kinetics Organisation Chart |url= http://www.stengg.com/our-business/land-systems/organisation-chart |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130716010504/http://www.stengg.com/our-business/land-systems/organisation-chart |archive-date= 16 July 2013 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March 2012, ST Kinetics is one of 6 companies that were blacklisted by India's [[Ministry of Defence (India)|Ministry of Defence]] for 10 years.<ref name=er-blacklists>{{cite news|url=http://www.eurasiareview.com/05032012-india-blacklists-four-international-defence-suppliers-over-scam/|title=India Blacklists Four International Defence Suppliers Over \"Scam\"|publisher=Eurasia Review|date=5 March 2012|access-date=5 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306130701/http://www.eurasiareview.com/05032012-india-blacklists-four-international-defence-suppliers-over-scam/|archive-date=6 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=ie-scam>{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/ordnance-scam-six-firms-barred-from-business-for-10-yrs/920456/|title=Ordnance scam: Six firms barred from business for 10 yrs|work=The Indian Express|date=5 March 2012}}</ref> The company was issued a [[show cause]] notice before it was blacklisted.<ref name=toi-bribery>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-05/india/31123453_1_defence-ministry-charge-sheet-blacklisted|title=Bribery scandal: Defence ministry blacklists six companies|work=The Times of India|date=5 March 2012}}</ref> On 25 May 2012, ST Kinetics filed a writ petition in the High Court of Delhi against the Indian Ministry of Defence (MoD) and the Indian Ordnance Factory Board (OFB), challenging the debarment order.<ref>{{cite news|title=ST Kinetics files writ petition against Indian authorities to challenge ban|newspaper=Business Times|date=28 May 2012|author=Malminderjit Singh}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=ST Engg maintains innocence over ST Kinetics debarment in India|newspaper=Singapore Business Review|date=28 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, ST Kinetics appointed Tata International as its distributor in Africa, thus expanding its distribution and customer support network for both its LeeBoy and TRXBUILD brands in 13 other countries.<ref>{{cite news|publisher= Singapore Business Review|date= 13 February 2013|title= ST Kinetics appoints TATA Engineering as distributor in Africa|url= http://sbr.com.sg/building-engineering/more-news/st-kinetics-appoints-tata-engineering-distributor-in-africa|access-date= 6 December 2013|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131210233758/http://sbr.com.sg/building-engineering/more-news/st-kinetics-appoints-tata-engineering-distributor-in-africa|archive-date= 10 December 2013|url-status= live}}</ref> In the same year, ST Kinetics established 2 new overseas subsidiaries in Brazil and Myanmar. In July, the company acquired Technicae Projetos e Servicos Automotivos for BRL1.04 million. This acquisition will expand the company's reach into Brazil's growing defence business.<ref>{{cite news|publisher= Shephard Press Limited|date= 23 July 2013|title= STK moves into Brazil|url= http://www.shephardmedia.com/news/mil-log/stk-moves-brazil/|access-date= 6 December 2013|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131210105110/http://www.shephardmedia.com/news/mil-log/stk-moves-brazil/|archive-date= 10 December 2013|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nEstablished in November 2013, the wholly owned subsidiary, Kinetics Automotive & Specialty Equipment Co., Ltd (KASE) was set up in Yangon, Myanmar. This Myanmar subsidiary will serve as a platform to introduce and support ST Kinetics' automotive and specialty vehicles products and services in Myanmar's burgeoning economy, as part of its plan to grow its commercial business in the country.<ref>{{cite news|work= Business Times|date= 19 November 2013|title= ST Engineering: ST Kinetics Sets Up Subsidiary in Yangon, Myanmar.|url= http://www.btinvest.com.sg/markets/news/72597.html?source=si_news|access-date= 6 December 2013|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131212141928/http://www.btinvest.com.sg/markets/news/72597.html?source=si_news|archive-date= 12 December 2013|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n\n==Ordnance==\n\n===M16S1 5.56 mm assault rifle===\n{{Main|M16S1}}\n\nThe M16S1 is the [[M16 rifle|M16A1 rifle]] made under license by STELS. It was the standard issue weapon of the [[Singapore Armed Forces]] and being replaced by the newer SAR 21 in most branches. It is, however, the standard issue weapon in reserve forces.\n\n===Ultimax 100 5.56 mm section automatic weapon===\n{{Main|Ultimax 100}}\n\nThe Ultimax 100 was designed by [[L. James Sullivan]], who previously had redesigned Eugene Stoner's 7.62&nbsp;mm AR10 assault rifle into a smaller 5.56&nbsp;mm version, the M16. The Ultimax 100 was considered by experts as one of the most manageable light machine guns in the world. The Ultimax 100 makes use of Sullivan's patented counter recoil mechanism that makes the Ultimax 100 \"not just a manageable full-automatic weapon, but a machine gun that can be aimed\".<ref name=\"JGRG2008-1\">Richard J (2008), page 399.</ref><ref name=\"JIDR1989-08\">Andrew C (August 1989).</ref>\n\n===SAR 21 5.56mm assault rifle===\n{{Main|SAR 21}}\n\nIn the mid 90s, the SAF decided to develop an indigenous rifle to replace the aging M16S1, most of which had been in service since the 70s. The other option was to procure new\u2014and more expensive\u2014weapons, with the chief contender being the M16A2. The [[Advanced Combat Rifle (Singapore)|Advanced Combat Rifle]] was conceived, and it eventually became the SAR 21. The SAR 21 is the first production assault rifle of its class to incorporate a built-in [[Laser applications#Laser sight|Laser Aiming Device (LAD)]] (powered by a single [[List of battery sizes|\"AA\" battery]]) as standard. The rifle incorporates various patented safety features, such as a [[Kevlar]] cheek plate and overpressure vent that protects the shooter in the unlikely event of a chamber explosion or catastrophic failure. It also has an integral 1.5\u00d7 [[optical]] [[telescopic sight|scope]] that is built into its carrying handle. The scope aids in target acquisition, particularly under low light conditions. The scope is factory-zeroed, and requires minimal further zeroing to suit different users. This minimizes non-training range time to zero the weapons and maximises live-firing training hours.<ref name=\"JGRG2008-2\">Richard J (2008), page 316.</ref><ref>{{Cite web |publisher= [[ST Engineering]] |access-date= 11 September 2007 |title= SAR 21 Product Brochure |url= http://www.stengg.com/upload/805FZ25kCHnhWIBPg9K.pdf |format= PDF |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080414141931/http://www.stengg.com/upload/805FZ25kCHnhWIBPg9K.pdf |archive-date= 14 April 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSee also:\n*[[SAR-80]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[5.56 mm]] [[assault rifle]]\n*[[SR-88]]&nbsp;\u2013 5.56&nbsp;mm assault rifle\n\n===BR18 (Formerly the Bullpup Multirole Combat Rifle)===\n{{Main|BR18}}\n[[File:STK BMCR.jpg|thumb|The Bullpup Multirole Combat Rifle on display at the [[Singapore Airshow]] 2014]]\n\nSingapore Technologies Kinetics Ltd unveiled the Bullpup Multirole Combat Rifle (BMCR) during the [[Singapore Airshow]] 2014.<ref name=\"ST Engineering\">{{cite news |publisher= [[ST Engineering]] |title= ST Kinetics' Solutions Put Warfighters Ahead of Their Game |url= http://www.stengg.com/press-centre/press-releases/st-kinetics-solutions-put-warfighters-ahead-of-their-game |year= 2014 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150222174823/http://www.stengg.com/press-centre/press-releases/st-kinetics-solutions-put-warfighters-ahead-of-their-game |archive-date= 22 February 2015 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Claimed to be the shortest bullpup rifle in the world with a 14.5-inch barrel, the BMCR provides ease and comfort for soldiers to manipulate in tight spaces.<ref>{{cite news |publisher= [[All4Shooters]] |title= EUROSATORY 2014: Singapore Technologies Kinetics introduces in Europe the BMCR bull-pup modular combat rifle! |url= http://www.all4shooters.com/en/news/rifles/2014/ST-Kinetics-BMCR-Bullpup-Modular-Combat-Rifle-Eurosatory-2014 |year= 2014 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140812230736/http://www.all4shooters.com/en/news/rifles/2014/ST-Kinetics-BMCR-Bullpup-Modular-Combat-Rifle-Eurosatory-2014/ |archive-date= 12 August 2014 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The BMCR is designed to fire NATO SS109 5.56mm ammunition and ST Kinetics' Extended Range 5.56mm ammunition, and come standard with MIL-STD-1913 Picatinny Rails at the three, six, nine and 12 o\u2019clock positions.<ref name=\"ST Engineering\"/> The rifle is fully ambidextrous and possesses flexibility for assault, marksman and suppressive roles.<ref name=\"MilitaryTechnology\">{{cite news |publisher= [[MilitaryTechnology]] |title= Singapore Airshow Photoblog: ST Engineering and Subsidiaries Exhibiting Innovation |url= http://www.miltechmag.com/2014/02/singapore-airshow-photoblog-st.html |year= 2014 |access-date= 23 July 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140801134334/http://www.miltechmag.com/2014/02/singapore-airshow-photoblog-st.html |archive-date= 1 August 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nThe weapon was renamed as the BR18, is scheduled to be in production by 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.janes.com/article/77744/singapore-airshow-2018-st-kinetics-launches-br18-5-56-mm-assault-rifle|title=Singapore Airshow 2018: ST Kinetics launches BR18 5.56 mm assault rifle \u2013 Jane's 360|website=www.janes.com|access-date=25 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425115708/http://www.janes.com/article/77744/singapore-airshow-2018-st-kinetics-launches-br18-5-56-mm-assault-rifle|archive-date=25 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Conventional Multirole Combat Rifle (CMCR)===\n{{Main|Conventional multirole combat rifle}}\n[[File:STK CMCR (12587721523).jpg|thumb|The Conventional Multirole Combat Rifle on display at the [[Singapore Airshow]] 2014]]\n\nThe 5.56mm Conventional Multirole Combat Rifle (CMCR) was released during the Singapore Airshow 2014.<ref name=\"ST Engineering\"/> Equipped with a unique adjustable and foldable buttstock, the CMCR provides ease and comfort for soldiers to manipulate in tight spaces. The CMCR is designed to fire NATO SS109 5.56mm ammunition and ST Kinetics' Extended Range 5.56mm ammunition, and come standard with MIL-STD-1913 Picatinny Rails at the three, six, nine and 12 o\u2019clock positions.<ref name=\"MilitaryTechnology\"/><ref>{{cite news|publisher= [[DefenseNews]] |title= ST Engineering Parades New Defense Products and Deals at Air Show\n|url= http://www.defensenews.com/article/20140211/DEFREG03/302110019/ST-Engineering-Parades-New-Defense-Products-Deals-Air-Show | year=2014}}</ref>\n\n===Compact Personal Weapon (CPW)===\n{{Main|ST Kinetics CPW}}\n\nThe CPW is a lightweight, multi-caliber [[Submachine Gun]] (SMG)/[[Personal Defense Weapon|Personal Defence Weapon]] (PDW) for [[Close Quarters Battle|Close Quarters Combat]] (CQB/CQC) operations as well as engagements up to 150m.\n\nThe CPW is available in [[9mm Parabellum]] (9\u00d719mm NATO) caliber for now and \"resembles an updated/modernized [[MP7A1]]\".<ref name = cpw>{{Cite web|url = http://www.defensereview.com/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=1188|title = ST Kinetics CPW (Compact Personal Weapon) Submachine Gun/PDW|publisher = Defense Review|author = David Crane}}</ref> The main differences are the angled pistol grip of the CPW for enhanced ergonomics and natural aiming, and a transparent rear magazine so that the operator can see the rounds remaining. Other features include a skeletonised trigger, a full-length [[Picatinny Rail|Mil-Std-1913 Picatinny top rail]] for mounting accessories such as optics and lasers, and a shorter bottom rail in front of the trigger guard for mounting a vertical foregrip.\n\nThe CPW weighs only 1.5&nbsp;kg empty/dry (2&nbsp;kg with a fully loaded 30-round 9&nbsp;mm magazine) and uses a unique bolt lever cam recoil mitigation system to control recoil and muzzle rise to increase target hits. Full-auto cyclic [[rate of fire]] is a relatively high 900 to 1100&nbsp;rpm.<ref name=brochure>{{Cite web |publisher= [[ST Engineering]] |access-date= 28 October 2008 |title= CPW Brochure |url= http://www.stengg.com/CoyCapPro/detail.aspx?pdid=399 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20081209062121/http://www.stengg.com/CoyCapPro/detail.aspx?pdid=399 |archive-date= 9 December 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===40 mm weapon and munition systems===\n{{Main|STK 40 AGL|STK 40 GL}}\n\nST Kinetics is one of the few producers of both 40&nbsp;mm munition and weapon systems.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= [[Defense News]] |title= Singapore Pushes To Dominate 40mm Grenade Market |url= http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=3379147 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The range of [[40 mm grenade|40&nbsp;mm rounds]] include low velocity, high velocity, less-than-lethal, camera,<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= [[ST Engineering]] |access-date= 11 September 2007 |title= 40mm SPARCS Product Brochure |url= http://www.stengg.com/upload/612TJKUY7dK8cTL7V66.pdf |format= PDF |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20060319220628/http://www.stengg.com/upload/612TJKUY7dK8cTL7V66.pdf |archive-date= 19 March 2006 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> self-destruct, airburst and enhanced blast insensitive explosive rounds. There are currently 3 weapon systems available, namely the 40&nbsp;mm Grenade Launcher (40GL), the 40&nbsp;mm Automatic Grenade Launcher (40AGL) and the 40&nbsp;mm Lightweight Automatic Grenade Launcher (40LWAGL, a portable version that is half the weight of conventional AGLs). The 40AGL was made in 1990, followed by the 40LWAGL in 2001 (previously called the 40&nbsp;mm Super Light Weight AGL). The 40AGL is mounted in combination with the 12.7-mm 50MG in the ST Kinetics' 40/50 cupola weapon system, installed on the M113 and Bionix. The 40AGL weighs 33&nbsp;kg without mount or ammunition. The objective of ST Kinetics in designing the 40LWAGL was to keep the grenade launcher's weight to below 20&nbsp;kg, or half the weight of conventional AGLs. Prototype weapons weighed around 14&nbsp;kg and small quantities have been sold to a few countries, including Sweden, mostly for evaluation. St Kinetics is also collaborating with Australia's [[Metal Storm Limited|Metal Storm]] and Electro Optics System to develop a new high-speed and recoilless 40&nbsp;mm grenade launcher called the Redback Lightweight.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Automatic+grenade+launchers:+new+automatic+40+mm+grenade+launchers...-a0171018007 | title=Automatic grenade launchers | publisher=Armada International | access-date=10 January 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080520124918/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Automatic+grenade+launchers%3a+new+automatic+40+mm+grenade+launchers...-a0171018007 | archive-date=20 May 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref> The company is reportedly the world's largest producer of the 40AGL, with more than 2,000 of the 40AGLs sold to the SAF and overseas customers.<ref>From bullet maker to defence tech giant, The Sunday Times, 30 December 2007, page 26</ref> In 2008, the company entered into a teaming agreement with [[Electro-Optic Systems]] (EOS) and [[Metal Storm Limited|Metal Storm]] (MS) to develop a 3-shot under-barrel grenade launcher called the [[Metal Storm Limited#3GL|3GL]].  The 3GL is intended to replace the M203 under barrel grenade launcher for most military rifles including the [[M16 rifle|M16]], [[AK-47]], [[SAR 21]] and [[Steyr AUG]].  It can also be detached to operate as a stand-alone weapon.<ref>{{cite news |publisher= [[Market Wire]] |title= Metal Storm Sets Weapons Commercialisation Path With ST Kinetics |url= http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_pwwi/is_/ai_n24330073 |year= 2008 |access-date= 15 December 2008 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20081212032131/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_pwwi/is_/ai_n24330073 |archive-date= 12 December 2008 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, Thales and ST Kinetics agreed to develop, manufacture and market ST Kinetics' 40mm low-velocity air-bursting ammunition for the Australian and New Zealand markets.<ref>{{cite news |publisher= [[IHS Jane's]] |title= DSEI 2013: Australian Munitions announces tie-ups with Diehl, ST Kinetics |url= http://www.janes.com/article/26947/dsei-2013-australian-munitions-announces-tie-ups-with-diehl-st-kinetics |year= 2013 |access-date= 6 December 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131210215731/http://www.janes.com/article/26947/dsei-2013-australian-munitions-announces-tie-ups-with-diehl-st-kinetics |archive-date= 10 December 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref> ST Kinetics also announced that the company secured a total of more than US$30 million worth of international orders from Canada and United States for its 40mm ammunition in October 2013.<ref>{{cite news |publisher= [[Land Warfare International]] |title= AUSA 2013: ST Kinetics secures ammo contracts |url= http://www.shephardmedia.com/news/landwarfareintl/ausa-2013-st-kinetics-secures-ammo-contracts/ |year= 2013 |access-date= 6 December 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131210105919/http://www.shephardmedia.com/news/landwarfareintl/ausa-2013-st-kinetics-secures-ammo-contracts/ |archive-date= 10 December 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===50MG machine gun===\n[[File:CIS 50 HMG.jpg|thumb|STK 50 HMG]]\n{{Main|STK 50MG}}\n\nThe 50MG was developed in the 1980s by CIS to replace the obsolete [[.50 BMG|{{Convert|12.7|mm|abbr=on}}]] [[M2 Browning|Browning M2HB machine guns]] used by the SAF. The CIS engineers learnt from the lesson of the unsuccessful American \"Dover Devil GPHMG\" programme, to create a modular weapon suited for modern tactical doctrines and production techniques. They succeeded and in 1988, CIS introduced the new machine gun and simply named it as the \"CIS 50MG\". The SAF used the 50MG in its infantry regiments and as a mounted weapon on armoured vehicles and naval craft. The STK 50MG is a gas-operated, air-cooled, belt-fed weapon. It has a quick-detachable barrel equipped with a carrying handle. The gun is operated using dual gas pistons, located in two gas tubes placed on either side of the barrel. The barrel is locked by means of a rotary bolt with multiple radial lugs that engages the barrel extension, eliminating the need for headspace adjustments. The STK 50MG utilizes the same \"constant recoil\" system used in the Ultimax 100. A unique feature of the 50MG is its dual belt-feed system that allows for fast and easy switching of ammunition from standard ball to armor-piercing [[Saboted light armor penetrator|Saboted Light Armor Penetrator (SLAP)]]. Such systems are more commonly used in modern automatic cannons.<ref name=\"JGRG2008-3\">Richard J (2008), page 398.</ref><ref name=\"JIDR1989-10\">Andrew C (October 1989).</ref><ref>{{Cite web|publisher=[[ST Engineering]]|access-date=12 April 2012|title=50MG Product Brochure|url=http://www.stengg.com/upload/1875jm6dmc40oAKikM8.pdf||url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090219082615/http://www.stengg.com/upload/1875jm6dmc40oAKikM8.pdf|archive-date=19 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n===120 mm Super Rapid Advanced Mortar System (SRAMS)===\nThe 120SRAMS is developed specifically for rapid and close range requirements of the battlefield. The semi-automatic Ammunition Transfer System and the patented Valve System in the breech mechanism provides an effective vent for the trapped air to let the bomb \"free-fall\" into the barrel. This reduces the projectile's in-bore travel and reportedly allows the 120SRAM to achieve the highest continuous firing rate of up to 18 rounds per minute\u20143 times faster than a conventional [[mortar (weapon)|mortar]] system which can fire up to 6 rounds per minute.<ref name= 120SRAM>{{Cite web |publisher= Defence Systems Daily |url= http://defence-data.com/dsei/pageds1019.htm |title= ST Kinetics unveil 120mm SRAMS and 40mm SLWAGL at DSEi |date= 12 September 2001 |access-date= 6 September 2007 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080202041757/http://defence-data.com/dsei/pageds1019.htm |archive-date= 2 February 2008 |url-status= live }}</ref> Recent product information has indicated the firing rate at a more modest 10 rounds per minute.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= ST Engineering |url= http://www.stengg.com/upload/620JKKP6Y94P4nl3aZf.pdf |format= PDF |title= 120SRAM Product Brochure |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110717020329/http://www.stengg.com/upload/620JKKP6Y94P4nl3aZf.pdf |archive-date= 17 July 2011 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The patented Cooling System is able to reduce the temperature that builds up in the barrel quickly to enable continuous firing without blockage. The patented Blast Diffuser reduces the blast overpressure by about 8 to 10 decibels. The 120SRAM is also currently the only system in the world with a recoil of less than 20 tonnes, which allows the 120SRAM to be mounted on board a 4\u00d74 wheeled vehicle. The 120SRAM has a navigation and positioning system, power gun drives and integrated with an automatic fire control system, which require just a 3-person crew to operate the weapon.<ref name= 120SRAM/>\n\n===FH-2000 field howitzer===\n{{Main|FH-2000}}\n\nThe FH-2000 is a 155&nbsp;mm 52-calibre towed [[howitzer]] gun and the \"first 52 calibre field howitzer in service and in series production\".<ref name= FAS>{{Cite web |url= http://www.fas.org/man/dod-101/sys/land/row/fh2000.htm |title= FH2000 |publisher= Federation of American Scientists |access-date= 7 January 2008 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20061015012456/http://www.fas.org/man/dod-101/sys/land/row/fh2000.htm |archive-date= 15 October 2006 |url-status= live }}</ref> Designed and built locally in Singapore by CIS, the FH-2000 deploys a crew of 8 and can use a low-powered self-propelled engine to travel at 10&nbsp;km/h without towing. It fires projectiles to a maximum range of 42&nbsp;km using special extended range ammunition that was field tested in New Zealand.\n\n===Pegasus 155mm lightweight howitzer===\n{{Main|SLWH Pegasus}}\n\nThe Pegasus is the world's first heli-portable 155&nbsp;mm 39 calibre self-propelled light howitzer, capable of offering aerial mobility for ''shoot and scoot''. The Pegasus' automatic ammunition loading system, advanced sight, lightweight material and innovative recoil management make the Pegasus highly survivable, fast to deploy and easy to use.\n\n===Primus self-propelled artillery===\n[[File:Primus 1.jpg|thumb|Primus on display]]\n{{Main|SSPH Primus}}\n\nThe Singapore Self-Propelled Howitzer 1 (SSPH 1) Primus is a [[self-propelled artillery]] unit armed with a 155&nbsp;mm [[howitzer]] jointly developed by the SAF, [http://www.dsta.gov.sg Defence Science and Technology Agency] (DSTA) and ST Kinetics. Primus provides the range, firepower and accuracy of the artillery while keeping its weight below 30 tons and width below 3m. Other self-propelled guns such as the U.S. ([[M109 Paladin]]), Britain's ([[AS-90|AS90 Braveheart]]), Japan's (Type 75) and Russia's (2S3M1) were either too heavy, at over 50 tons, or too wide, beyond 3m, for the tropical rainforest and swampy terrains. The chassis is based on the proven [[United Defense]] [[M109 Paladin|M109 155&nbsp;mm self-propelled howitzer]], with a new power pack similar to the one fitted on the [[Bionix AFV|Bionix infantry fighting vehicle]] (IFV). The power pack consists of a [[Detroit Diesel Corporation]] [[Series 92|6V 92TIA]] diesel engine developing 550&nbsp;hp coupled to a [[General Dynamics]] Land Systems HMPT-500-3EC fully automatic transmission. The maximum road speed of the Primus is 50&nbsp;km/h, with an operating range of 350&nbsp;km, its combat weight is of 28.3 tons allows it to use the SAF 's current military bridging systems. The Primus could be deployed by the future [[Airbus A400M]] Transport aircraft.\n\n===Bionix armoured fighting vehicle===\n{{Main|Bionix AFV}}\n\nThe Bionix was the first local [[armoured fighting vehicle]], designed and developed by ST Kinetics. It is a medium-weight tracked vehicle, weighing between twenty-two to twenty-eight tonnes, to replace the aging M-113A2 armoured personnel carriers. The Bionix was commissioned by the SAF in September 1997 and operated under the 42nd Battalion of the Singapore Armoured Regiment ([[42 SAR]]). During the commissioning parade in July 1999, then Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Defence, Dr Tony Tan, declared the Bionix IFV to be \"a highly effective indigenous armoured vehicle\".<ref>{{cite press release |publisher= Ministry of Defence, Singapore |title= SAF's First Infantry Fighting Vehicle Armoured Battle Group is Operational |date= 30 July 1999 |url= http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/news_and_events/nr/1999/jul/30jul99_nr.html |access-date= 31 December 2007 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181215171823/http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/news_and_events/nr/1999/jul/30jul99_nr.html |archive-date= 15 December 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref> The Bionix was eventually succeeded by the Bionix II, which was jointly developed by the SAF, the Defence Science and Technology Agency (DSTA), and ST Kinetics.<ref>{{Cite web|publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Singapore)]] |url=http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/mindef_websites/topics/Weapons/bx2/about.html |title=About Bionix II |date=30 November 2006 |access-date=6 September 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071006092748/http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/mindef_websites/topics/Weapons/bx2/about.html |archive-date=6 October 2007 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Bronco all-terrain tracked carrier===\n{{Main|Bronco All Terrain Tracked Carrier}}\n\nThe Bronco is manufactured by ST Kinetics for the Singaporean Army and in small amounts as an UOR for the British Army in Afghanistan. The company is also manufacturing the firefighter and other civilian variants of the ATTC under its U.S. subsidiary, Hackney<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rescueleader.com/products/attv.htm|title=Hackney Emergency Vehicles|website=www.rescueleader.com|access-date=28 December 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080101040819/http://www.rescueleader.com/products/attv.htm|archive-date=1 January 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> where it is positioned as a disaster recovery vehicle with its ability to access uneven and soft terrains impassable to normal vehicles after earthquakes, floods or other major urban catastrophes. Another commercial variant, the All Terrain Tracked Emergency-Engineering Car \u5168\u5730\u5f62\u5c65\u5e26\u5f0f\u5de5\u7a0b\u62a2\u9669,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jonyang.com/2007/english/products/detail.asp?findid=12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080131231234/http://www.jonyang.com/2007/english/products/detail.asp?findid=12|url-status=dead|title=Product introduction-All terrain tracked emergencyengineering car-Products-Guizhou Jonyang Kinetics Co., Ltd|archive-date=31 January 2008}}</ref> is also under development by its China subsidiary, GJK, in a bid to leverage on China's cost advantage. Competition would include the Russian Vityaz DT-(10/20/30)P models<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cardatabase.net/search/search.php?manufacturer=Vityaz|title=Cardatabase.net \u2013 Car photo search \u2013 Vityaz|website=www.cardatabase.net|access-date=28 December 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080202005400/http://www.cardatabase.net/search/search.php?manufacturer=Vityaz|archive-date=2 February 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> and BAe Hagglunds' [[BVS10]].\n\n===Terrex AV81 8\u00d78 AFV===\n{{Main|Terrex}}\n\nThe Terrex AV81 is an [[armoured fighting vehicle]] weighing between 25 and 30 tons an 8\u00d78 wheeled chassis and modern armour. Multiple weapon platforms are supported, including both the remote and overhead weapons stations. The Terrex's modular design allows for different level of armour protection and weapon systems. It is designed to be air-portable by [[C-130]]s or equivalent cargo aircraft. The Terrex uses a patented independent [[double wishbone suspension]], which greatly improves ground mobility and comfort during rides over rough terrains. The use of automatic traction control and the capacity for large footprint off-road tyres enables the Terrex to reach high speed on soft ground. The vehicle has a double hull with an external [[V-hull]] that improves mine blast survivability. Add-on armour provides further protection for troops. It is also capable of providing full chemical, biological and nuclear protection in extreme operational conditions. The baseline configuration is fully [[Amphibious vehicle|amphibious]]. Two water jets mounted on either side at the back of the hull propel the vehicle through water at 10&nbsp;km/h. Initially developed for export sales from the number of emerging wheeled armoured vehicle requirements including U.S. [[Brigade combat team|Interim Brigade Combat Team]] (IBCT) concept, which calls for the need of wheeled armoured fighting vehicles (AFV) as opposed to tracked AFVs. In 2006, the SAF decided to purchase 135 units to replace their aging [[Cadillac Gage Commando|V-200]] armoured vehicles. The [[Indonesian Army]] also indicated plans to purchase 420 units and to produce the Terrex under license locally.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= \u4e2d\u56fd\u56fd\u9632\u62a5 |url= http://jczs.sina.com.cn/2006-03-20/0942358456.html |title= \u65b0\u52a0\u5761\u7814\u5236\"\u7279\u62c9\u514b\u65af\"AV81\u88c5\u7532\u6b65\u6218\u8f66 |date= 20 March 2006 |access-date= 2 January 2008 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20060425042927/http://jczs.sina.com.cn/2006-03-20/0942358456.html |archive-date= 25 April 2006 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |publisher= Strategy Page |url= http://www.strategypage.com/dls/articles/Terrex-The-Terrific-9-22-2009.asp |title= Terrex the Terrific |date= 22 September 2009 |access-date= 15 November 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110616184300/http://www.strategypage.com/dls/articles/Terrex-The-Terrific-9-22-2009.asp |archive-date= 16 June 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===Hunter armoured fighting vehicle===\n{{Main|Hunter AFV}}\n\nThe Hunter was jointly developed with [[Defence Science and Technology Agency]], and the [[Singapore Army]]. Intended to replace the Singapore Army's aging Ultra [[M113 Armored Personnel Carrier|M113]] [[armoured personnel carrier]]s, it was commissioned in 2019. It is the Singapore Army's first fully digitalised platform and is designed to provide armoured forces with enhanced capabilities to operate more effectively and efficiently in various phases of military operations.\n\n===Other military and para-military products===\n;Munitions\n*81&nbsp;mm [[Mortar (weapon)|Mortar]]\n*120&nbsp;mm Mortar\n*155&nbsp;mm Large Calibre Munition\n*[[Hand grenade]]s\n*[[Pyrotechnics]]\n\n;Small arms\n*7.62&nbsp;mm [[General Purpose Machine Gun]] (GPMG)\n\n;Platform\n[[File:Singapore Army Mark 2 Light Strike Vehicle on display at the National Museum of Singapore - 20140223.jpg|thumb|right|Spider New Generation Light Strike Vehicle]]\n*[[Light Strike Vehicle (Singapore)|Spider New Generation (New Gen)]] Light Strike Vehicle (LSV)\n*Light Armoured Multi-Role Vehicle (LAMV)\n*Mini All Terrain Vehicle (MATV)\n*Asset Maintenance\n*[[Contract Manufacturing]]\n\n;[[Homeland Security]] Solutions\n*Rapid Deployment Solution\n*Security Tamper Evident Bags (STEB)\n*Demul X Biological & Chemical Decontamination System (BCDS)\n*Integrated Mail Screening System (IMSS)\n*Demilitarisation services (Demil)\n*Analysis, Test and Evaluation (AT&E)\n*Advanced Logistics Proactive Solutions (ALPS)\n\n==Commercial equipment==\nST Kinetics started on the commercial vehicle business in 2004 and has yet to establish a presence in the global marketplace even though its subsidiaries are well-established brands within their respective countries. In 2008, ST Kinetics began to market selected commercial vehicles and the hybrid drive solutions as ecological products.\n\n===Construction vehicles===\nST Kinetics' BZK JV in China produces fixed and articulated off-road dumptrucks ranging from 20 to 52 ton. BZK also produces complementary products like cement carriers and mixers and [[Shunt truck|terminal port tractors]] for container ports operation. Jonyang excavators has been in operation in China and surrounding regions over 30 years, and manufactured both wheeled and tracked hydraulic excavators. LeeBoy has been a leading producer of commercial asphalt pavers and motor-graders since 1964 in the U.S.\n\n===Distribution vehicles===\nHackney and Kidron are aluminium and refrigerated truck bodies manufacturers respectively in the U.S. Hackney beverage trucks has been marketing its optimised compartmentalisation and light-weight aluminium bodies as means to lower lifecycle costs to the operators. Kidron has pioneered multi-temperature distribution with its Adjustable Compartmentalised Multi-temperature System (ACMT) of movable partitions. The ACMT allows configuration of loads requiring different temperature and compartment sizes.\n\n===Urban and emergency vehicles===\nHackney Emergency also designs emergency vehicles for the U.S. markets such as firetrucks and HAZMAT vehicles.  ST Kinetics itself also produces a series of urban vehicles, such as [[ambulance]]s, [[HAZMAT]] vehicles, [[fire engines]], terminal prime movers for local use, mostly for local use by the [[Singapore Civil Defence Force]] and the [[Singapore Police Force]].\n\nIn addition, ST Kinetics is the sole importer and distributor of [[MAN Truck & Bus]] vehicles within Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stengg.com/en/products-solutions/man-truck-and-bus|title=ST Engineering \u2013 MAN Truck and Bus|access-date=9 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709020603/https://www.stengg.com/en/products-solutions/man-truck-and-bus|archive-date=9 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Automotive services==\nThe automotive services have continued since the SAE days to become the Total Support & Services arm of the present day ST Kinetics. ST Kinetics continue to provide MRO services to military, commercial and general customers.\n\n===MRO services for military vehicles===\nAs part of the integrated logistics support system for the major platforms, ST Kinetics has established the MRO services under its Kinetics Integrated Services (KIS) arm. KIS also provides maintenance of the existing SAF fleet of MAN trucks.\n\n===Component servicing===\nSDDA is both Detroit Diesel and Allison transmission's Asia distribution centre as well as a service hub for the overhaul of automotive engines, Allison transmissions and fuel injection pumps, and the servicing of electrical, electronic, hydraulic & mechanical components.\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Bibliography\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Richard Jones|last2=Andrew White|title=Jane's Guns Recognition Guide|year=2008|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|isbn=978-0-00-726645-6}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Andrew|first=C Tillman|date=August 1989|title=IDR test report: Ultimax light machine gun&nbsp;\u2014 the ultimate in controllability|journal=[[Jane's International Defence Review]]|pages=1093\u20131095|issn=0020-6512}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Andrew|first=C Tillman|date=October 1989|title=IDR test report: Singapore's Lightweight Heavy|journal=Jane's International Defence Review|pages=1377\u20131380|issn=0020-6512|url=http://i295.photobucket.com/albums/mm137/spyder-album2/Singapore/CIS-50MG-2.jpg|accessdate=12 April 2012}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.stengg.com/en/land-systems/ ST Engineering Land Systems official website]\n\n{{Singapore-designed weapons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:St Kinetics}}\n[[Category:Defence companies]]\n[[Category:Engineering companies of Singapore]]\n[[Category:Military vehicle manufacturers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = ST Engineering Land Systems\n| logo                = https://www.google.com/search?q=st+kinetics&rlz=1C1CHBD_enSG893SG893&sxsrf=ALeKk0298f1i7X4U4vVo4P7UzyAkpzQGVA:1587459902201&tbm=isch&source=iu&ictx=1&fir=8gbGKWpcZbY6xM%253A%252CDlacC9jFD5pEAM%252C%252Fm%252F0g0gr3&vet=1&usg=AI4_-kRRLEbI65jJ4BbL1gAoI4GBmPP5gA&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjnjcP8lPnoAhUIU30KHcsUCV8Q_B0wDXoECAwQAw#imgrc=8gbGKWpcZbY6xM:\n| type                = [[Subsidiary]] of ST Engineering\n| foundation          = {{start date and age|df=y|1967|01|27}} as the Chartered Industries of Singapore (CIS)\n| key_people          = Dr. Lee Tsien Long, President STELS<ref>{{cite web|title=Biography of Dr LEE Shiang Long, President, Land Systems|url=https://www.stengg.com/media/617909/bio-dr-lee-shiang-long-6-jun-2019.pdf|date=6 June 2019|archive-url=https://webcache.googleusercontent.com/search?q=cache:WB8R6zItcbsJ:https://www.stengg.com/media/617909/bio-dr-lee-shiang-long-6-jun-2019.pdf|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| location            = Singapore\n| industry            = [[Arms industry|Defence]]<br/> Commercial Vehicles<br/> Automotive Services\n| products            = [[Ammunition]]<br/> [[Firearm]]s <br/> [[Weapon]]s <br/>Armored vehicles, [[IFV]]/[[Armoured patrol vehicle|APV]]<br/> Vehicle MRO Services <br/> [[Emergency vehicle]]s <br/> [[Truck|Distribution Vehicles]] <br/> [[Heavy Equipment|Construction Equipment]]s <br/> Testing Services\n| revenue             = > S$1.43b (2019)\n| num_employees       = > 7,000 (2013)\n| parent              = [[ST Engineering]]\n| homepage            = [http://www.stengg.com/]\n}}\n\n'''Singapore Technologies Land Systems Ltd (STELS, formerly ST Kinetics)''', in [[Singapore]], is a strategic business area of [[ST Engineering]] and handles land systems and specialty vehicles.\n\nIn 2000, ST Engineering acquired the Chartered Industries of Singapore (CIS) through ST Automotive, a subsidiary of ST Engineering, and the new company was named ST Kinetics. Given the initial charter of CIS to support the local defence requirements, the main defence customer of ST Kinetics remains as the [[Singapore Armed Forces]] (SAF).\n\nBesides manufacturing [[small arms]] and [[munitions]], some of STELS' key military products include the [[SAR 21]] assault rifle, the [[Bionix AFV]], the [[Bronco All Terrain Tracked Carrier]] and the [[Terrex ICV|Terrex APC]]. These weapons and ammunition are often made to U.S. or NATO specifications for export. The company holds a number of subsidiaries overseas, mainly in the U.S., Canada, China and India.\n\nRecent [[acquisitions]] between 2004 and 2009 have seen new construction equipment, specialised bodies and trailers for urban services being brought into ST Kinetics' stable of products, which was previously dominated by military weapons and platforms. Together with the other ST Engineering companies, STELS is part of the Singapore Defence Ecosystem of users, developers and producers in support of the Third Generation SAF.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= [[Jane's Defence Weekly]] |title= Industry Briefing&nbsp;\u2014 Singapore: Defence Ecosystem |access-date= 15 January 2008 |year= 2006 |url= http://www.dso.org.sg/data/JDW_Feb15_Defence_Ecosystem_210220061215.pdf |format= PDF |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20070412014859/http://www.dso.org.sg/data/JDW_Feb15_Defence_Ecosystem_210220061215.pdf |archive-date= 12 April 2007 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n===1967\u20131986: Rapid growth and expansion===\nCIS was originally incorporated on 27 January 1967, when it started out by producing [[Weapon|ordnance]] for the SAF.<ref name=milestones>{{Cite web |publisher= [[ST Engineering]] |title= Milestones |access-date= 26 December 2007 |year= 2006 |url= http://www.stengg.com/kinetics/historymilestones.aspx |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080118173832/http://www.stengg.com/kinetics/historymilestones.aspx |archive-date= 18 January 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> CIS' first product was the [[5.56\u00d745mm NATO]] round; other CIS products include the license-built [[Colt's Manufacturing Company|Colt]] [[M16 rifle|M16S1]] (equivalent to the M16A1), and locally designed weapons such as the [[Ultimax 100]] SAW, the [[SAR-80]] and the [[SR-88]] assault rifles. Several other companies were formed under CIS over the span of the next 2 decades, with the expansion of the defence business, such as Unicorn International (UI) in 1971, Ordnance & Development Engineering (ODE) in 1973, Singapore Test Services (STS) in 1980 and Chartered Chemicals (CCI) in 1982.\n\nShortly after the formation of CIS, the Defence Minister, Dr [[Goh Keng Swee]], went on to set up several other government-linked defence industries to provide indigenous support for the SAF. One of them was Singapore Automotive Engineering (SAE). SAE was to support automotive-related services for the SAF, and its first immediate task was to service and maintain a fleet of [[Cadillac Gage Commando|V200]] armored vehicles.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= [[National University of Singapore|NUS]] |title= Refer to Year 1970 |url= http://www.tdsi.nus.edu.sg/Downloads/Staff/MB_LPC.html |access-date= 3 January 2008 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20071230234028/http://www.tdsi.nus.edu.sg/Downloads/Staff/MB_LPC.html |archive-date= 30 December 2007 |url-status= live }}</ref> By 1982, amidst a young, thriving Singapore economy and having built up its capability in automotive servicing and standards, SAE saw the potential in the commercial sector and decided to incorporate SAE Inspection Centre for vehicle inspection and servicing. The following year, Singapore Commuters, a taxi service, was formed.\n\n===1987\u20131996: Reformation===\nOn 20 August 1991, SAE was publicly listed on the [[Singapore Stock Exchange]].<ref name= milestones/> In the same year, SAE was renamed Singapore Technologies Automotive (ST Auto). STA Detroit Diesel-Allison was formed to take on the maintenance of the Detroit diesel engines and Allison transmission used in the Bionix as well as to distribute the Detroit Diesel parts in the Asian region.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= ST Engineering |title= Company profile SDDA |url= http://www.stengg.com/aboutus/company_detail.aspx?cypid=5&cyid=23 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080202135436/http://www.stengg.com/aboutus/company_detail.aspx?cypid=5&cyid=23 |archive-date= 2 February 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSingapore Commuters was merged with Singapore Airport Services Ltd (SABS Taxi Ltd) and Singapore Bus Service Taxi Pte Ltd (SBS Taxi Pte Ltd) to form CitiCab in April 1995.<ref>{{Cite web|publisher=CityCab |title=Company Profile |url=http://www.citycab.com.sg/abtus/cc_history.htm |access-date=31 December 2007 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071224065919/http://www.citycab.com.sg/abtus/cc_history.htm |archive-date=24 December 2007 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref> By 1996, CIS through its various subsidiaries were producing various ordnance for the SAF and for export overseas. Chartered Ammunition Industries (CAI) was producing small, medium and large caliber ammunition, explosives, pyrotechnics and anti-tank weapons. ODE was producing medium to large caliber weapon systems (mortars, medium caliber cannons, FH88, FH2000). Chartered Firearms Industries (CFI) was producing infantry and crew-served weapons, including the SR88A assault rifle, Ultimax 100, 7.62&nbsp;mm GPMG, the 40&nbsp;mm grenade launchers, and the 40/50 Cupola Weapon system. Allied Ordnance of Singapore (AOS) was offering a range of advanced low-level air defence equipment, including the 40&nbsp;mm L70 air defense gun system, and missile and Optronic fire control systems.\n\nFor the automotive business, ST Auto took on the AMX-13 Light Tank upgrading project, and refurbished the M113 APC, Commando V100 and V200 armored vehicles, LARC V amphibious. ST Auto also signed a contract with the SAF to overhaul, maintain and repair its military ground equipment. Singapore Test Services by then was offering specialized tests and inspection services to both military and civilian customers.<ref name= FAS/>\n\n===1997\u2013present: Reinvention===\nIn 1997, ST Auto, together with Singapore Technologies Aerospace Ltd (ST Aerospace), Singapore Technologies Electronics Ltd (ST Electronics), and Singapore Technologies Marine Ltd (ST Marine), were merged to form the present ST Engineering.<ref>{{cite press release |publisher= ST Engineering |title= Joint Announcement&nbsp;\u2014 Singapore Technologies Engineering Companies Amalgamating for Strength |date= 28 August 1997 |url= http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=480 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080202135452/http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=480 |archive-date= 2 February 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn October 1999, ST Engineering acquired CIS at S$78 M.<ref>{{cite press release |publisher= ST Engineering |title= ST Engg Acquires Chartered Industries of Singapore (CIS) |date= 22 October 1999 |url= http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=243 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080202135420/http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=243 |archive-date= 2 February 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> ST Auto and CIS were merged in Feb 2000 to form ST Kinetics.<ref>{{cite press release |title= ST Engg Positions for Land Systems Market |date= 18 February 2000 |url= http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=461 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080202135425/http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=461 |archive-date= 2 February 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The following year, ST Kinetics reorganised itself into 3 divisions, namely Automotive; Munitions and Weapons; and Services, Trading and Others.<ref>{{Cite web | title = Retrospective: Land System, see page 26 | url = http://www.stengg.com/investorelations/pdf/ar2001.pdf | format = PDF | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20070226135511/http://www.stengg.com/investorelations/pdf/ar2001.pdf | archive-date = 26 February 2007 | df = dmy-all }}</ref> A series of flagship products were developed by the early 21st century, including the SAR21 assault rifle, the Primus 155mm self-propelled artillery gun, the Pegasus 155&nbsp;mm lightweight howitzer, the Bronco All-Terrain Tracked Carrier and the Terrex 8\u00d78 Armoured Personnel Carrier.\n\nST Kinetics went on to invest in several companies overseas to enhance its engineering capabilities. An example was the acquisition of Silvatech Industries Inc in July 2006, a Canadian company specialising in forestry equipment, and renaming it as Kinetics Drive Solutions (KDS) in August 2006<ref>{{cite press release |publisher= ST Kinetics |date= 4 August 2006 |title= Change of Subsidiary Name |url= http://www.stengg.com/press-centre/press-releases/change-of-subsidiary-name-1 |archive-url= https://archive.is/20130411213412/http://www.stengg.com/press-centre/press-releases/change-of-subsidiary-name-1 |url-status= dead |archive-date= 11 April 2013 }}</ref> to focus on the [[Infinitely Variable Transmission]]s (IVT) that Silvatech had developed for its forestry equipment.\n\n2003 was the year ST Kinetics decided to venture into the new commercial vehicles business to leverage on the engineering and fabrication capabilities it has acquired through the military vehicle projects. That year, ST Kinetics went into an equal-share joint venture with Beijing Heavy Duty Truck Plant (BHDTP) to form the Beijing Zhonghuan Kinetics Heavy Vehicles Co. Ltd (BZK).<ref>{{cite press release |publisher= ST Kinetics |date= 26 March 2004 |title= Beijing JV Company Obtains Regulatory Approvals |url= http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=612 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080202135457/http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=612 |archive-date= 2 February 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, ST Kinetics acquired Specialized Vehicles Corporation in U.S. along with its Hackney and Kidron brands, 2 market leaders in the U.S. beverage truck bodies business.<ref name=press_828>{{cite press release |publisher= ST Kinetics |date= 1 August 2005 |title= ST Engineering Acquires Specialized Vehicles Corporations |url= http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=828 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080202135509/http://www.stengg.com/pressroom/press_releases_read.aspx?paid=828 |archive-date= 2 February 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> In the same year, ST Kinetics signed a 60\u201340 joint venture with Guiyang City Industrial Investment Holding Corporation (GIIHC) to form Guizhou Jonyang Kinetics Co., Ltd. (GJK) that manufactures excavators,<ref name= press_828/> and set up STAR Guangzhou and STAR Hangzhou.\n\nIn June 2006, ST Kinetics wholly acquired Leeboy through ST Engineering's U.S. subsidiary, VT Systems. Leeboy is a U.S. industry leader in commercial class asphalt pavers.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= Leeboy |title= Company Profile |url= http://www.leeboy.com/showcontent.aspx?id=121 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080201173216/http://www.leeboy.com/showcontent.aspx?id=121 |archive-date= 1 February 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, ST Kinetics reorganised itself into 2 business groups. The Defence Business Group handles all military business and the Commercial Business Group manages the commercial businesses.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= ST Kinetics |title= ST Kinetics Organisation Chart |url= http://www.stengg.com/our-business/land-systems/organisation-chart |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20130716010504/http://www.stengg.com/our-business/land-systems/organisation-chart |archive-date= 16 July 2013 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nOn 5 March 2012, ST Kinetics is one of 6 companies that were blacklisted by India's [[Ministry of Defence (India)|Ministry of Defence]] for 10 years.<ref name=er-blacklists>{{cite news|url=http://www.eurasiareview.com/05032012-india-blacklists-four-international-defence-suppliers-over-scam/|title=India Blacklists Four International Defence Suppliers Over \"Scam\"|publisher=Eurasia Review|date=5 March 2012|access-date=5 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306130701/http://www.eurasiareview.com/05032012-india-blacklists-four-international-defence-suppliers-over-scam/|archive-date=6 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=ie-scam>{{cite news|url=http://www.indianexpress.com/news/ordnance-scam-six-firms-barred-from-business-for-10-yrs/920456/|title=Ordnance scam: Six firms barred from business for 10 yrs|work=The Indian Express|date=5 March 2012}}</ref> The company was issued a [[show cause]] notice before it was blacklisted.<ref name=toi-bribery>{{cite news|url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-03-05/india/31123453_1_defence-ministry-charge-sheet-blacklisted|title=Bribery scandal: Defence ministry blacklists six companies|work=The Times of India|date=5 March 2012}}</ref> On 25 May 2012, ST Kinetics filed a writ petition in the High Court of Delhi against the Indian Ministry of Defence (MoD) and the Indian Ordnance Factory Board (OFB), challenging the debarment order.<ref>{{cite news|title=ST Kinetics files writ petition against Indian authorities to challenge ban|newspaper=Business Times|date=28 May 2012|author=Malminderjit Singh}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=ST Engg maintains innocence over ST Kinetics debarment in India|newspaper=Singapore Business Review|date=28 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2013, ST Kinetics appointed Tata International as its distributor in Africa, thus expanding its distribution and customer support network for both its LeeBoy and TRXBUILD brands in 13 other countries.<ref>{{cite news|publisher= Singapore Business Review|date= 13 February 2013|title= ST Kinetics appoints TATA Engineering as distributor in Africa|url= http://sbr.com.sg/building-engineering/more-news/st-kinetics-appoints-tata-engineering-distributor-in-africa|access-date= 6 December 2013|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131210233758/http://sbr.com.sg/building-engineering/more-news/st-kinetics-appoints-tata-engineering-distributor-in-africa|archive-date= 10 December 2013|url-status= live}}</ref> In the same year, ST Kinetics established 2 new overseas subsidiaries in Brazil and Myanmar. In July, the company acquired Technicae Projetos e Servicos Automotivos for BRL1.04 million. This acquisition will expand the company's reach into Brazil's growing defence business.<ref>{{cite news|publisher= Shephard Press Limited|date= 23 July 2013|title= STK moves into Brazil|url= http://www.shephardmedia.com/news/mil-log/stk-moves-brazil/|access-date= 6 December 2013|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131210105110/http://www.shephardmedia.com/news/mil-log/stk-moves-brazil/|archive-date= 10 December 2013|url-status= live}}</ref>\n\nEstablished in November 2013, the wholly owned subsidiary, Kinetics Automotive & Specialty Equipment Co., Ltd (KASE) was set up in Yangon, Myanmar. This Myanmar subsidiary will serve as a platform to introduce and support ST Kinetics' automotive and specialty vehicles products and services in Myanmar's burgeoning economy, as part of its plan to grow its commercial business in the country.<ref>{{cite news|work= Business Times|date= 19 November 2013|title= ST Engineering: ST Kinetics Sets Up Subsidiary in Yangon, Myanmar.|url= http://www.btinvest.com.sg/markets/news/72597.html?source=si_news|access-date= 6 December 2013|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131212141928/http://www.btinvest.com.sg/markets/news/72597.html?source=si_news|archive-date= 12 December 2013|url-status= dead}}</ref>\n\n==Ordnance==\n\n===M16S1 5.56 mm assault rifle===\n{{Main|M16S1}}\n\nThe M16S1 is the [[M16 rifle|M16A1 rifle]] made under license by STELS. It was the standard issue weapon of the [[Singapore Armed Forces]] and being replaced by the newer SAR 21 in most branches. It is, however, the standard issue weapon in reserve forces.\n\n===Ultimax 100 5.56 mm section automatic weapon===\n{{Main|Ultimax 100}}\n\nThe Ultimax 100 was designed by [[L. James Sullivan]], who previously had redesigned Eugene Stoner's 7.62&nbsp;mm AR10 assault rifle into a smaller 5.56&nbsp;mm version, the M16. The Ultimax 100 was considered by experts as one of the most manageable light machine guns in the world. The Ultimax 100 makes use of Sullivan's patented counter recoil mechanism that makes the Ultimax 100 \"not just a manageable full-automatic weapon, but a machine gun that can be aimed\".<ref name=\"JGRG2008-1\">Richard J (2008), page 399.</ref><ref name=\"JIDR1989-08\">Andrew C (August 1989).</ref>\n\n===SAR 21 5.56 assault rifle===\n{{Main|SAR 21}}\n\nIn the mid 90s, the SAF decided to develop an indigenous rifle to replace the aging M16S1, most of which had been in service since the 70s. The other option was to procure new\u2014and more expensive\u2014weapons, with the chief contender being the M16A2. The [[Advanced Combat Rifle (Singapore)|Advanced Combat Rifle]] was conceived, and it eventually became the SAR 21. The SAR 21 is the first production assault rifle of its class to incorporate a built-in [[Laser applications#Laser sight|Laser Aiming Device (LAD)]] (powered by a single [[List of battery sizes|\"AA\" battery]]) as standard. The rifle incorporates various patented safety features, such as a [[Kevlar]] cheek plate and overpressure vent that protects the shooter in the unlikely event of a chamber explosion or catastrophic failure. It also has an integral 1.5\u00d7 [[optical]] [[telescopic sight|scope]] that is built into its carrying handle. The scope aids in target acquisition, particularly under low light conditions. The scope is factory-zeroed, and requires minimal further zeroing to suit different users. This minimizes non-training range time to zero the weapons and maximises live-firing training hours.<ref name=\"JGRG2008-2\">Richard J (2008), page 316.</ref><ref>{{Cite web |publisher= [[ST Engineering]] |access-date= 11 September 2007 |title= SAR 21 Product Brochure |url= http://www.stengg.com/upload/805FZ25kCHnhWIBPg9K.pdf |format= PDF |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080414141931/http://www.stengg.com/upload/805FZ25kCHnhWIBPg9K.pdf |archive-date= 14 April 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nSee also:\n*[[SAR-80]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[5.56 mm]] [[assault rifle]]\n*[[SR-88]]&nbsp;\u2013 5.56&nbsp;mm assault rifle\n\n===BR18 (Formerly the Bullpup Multirole Combat Rifle)===\n{{Main|BR18}}\n[[File:STK BMCR.jpg|thumb|The Bullpup Multirole Combat Rifle on display at the [[Singapore Airshow]] 2014]]\n\nSingapore Technologies Kinetics Ltd unveiled the Bullpup Multirole Combat Rifle (BMCR) during the [[Singapore Airshow]] 2014.<ref name=\"ST Engineering\">{{cite news |publisher= [[ST Engineering]] |title= ST Kinetics' Solutions Put Warfighters Ahead of Their Game |url= http://www.stengg.com/press-centre/press-releases/st-kinetics-solutions-put-warfighters-ahead-of-their-game |year= 2014 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20150222174823/http://www.stengg.com/press-centre/press-releases/st-kinetics-solutions-put-warfighters-ahead-of-their-game |archive-date= 22 February 2015 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> Claimed to be the shortest bullpup rifle in the world with a 14.5-inch barrel, the BMCR provides ease and comfort for soldiers to manipulate in tight spaces.<ref>{{cite news |publisher= [[All4Shooters]] |title= EUROSATORY 2014: Singapore Technologies Kinetics introduces in Europe the BMCR bull-pup modular combat rifle! |url= http://www.all4shooters.com/en/news/rifles/2014/ST-Kinetics-BMCR-Bullpup-Modular-Combat-Rifle-Eurosatory-2014 |year= 2014 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140812230736/http://www.all4shooters.com/en/news/rifles/2014/ST-Kinetics-BMCR-Bullpup-Modular-Combat-Rifle-Eurosatory-2014/ |archive-date= 12 August 2014 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The BMCR is designed to fire NATO SS109 5.56mm ammunition and ST Kinetics' Extended Range 5.56mm ammunition, and come standard with MIL-STD-1913 Picatinny Rails at the three, six, nine and 12 o\u2019clock positions.<ref name=\"ST Engineering\"/> The rifle is fully ambidextrous and possesses flexibility for assault, marksman and suppressive roles.<ref name=\"MilitaryTechnology\">{{cite news |publisher= [[MilitaryTechnology]] |title= Singapore Airshow Photoblog: ST Engineering and Subsidiaries Exhibiting Innovation |url= http://www.miltechmag.com/2014/02/singapore-airshow-photoblog-st.html |year= 2014 |access-date= 23 July 2014 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140801134334/http://www.miltechmag.com/2014/02/singapore-airshow-photoblog-st.html |archive-date= 1 August 2014 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nThe weapon was renamed as the BR18, is scheduled to be in production by 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.janes.com/article/77744/singapore-airshow-2018-st-kinetics-launches-br18-5-56-mm-assault-rifle|title=Singapore Airshow 2018: ST Kinetics launches BR18 5.56 mm assault rifle \u2013 Jane's 360|website=www.janes.com|access-date=25 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425115708/http://www.janes.com/article/77744/singapore-airshow-2018-st-kinetics-launches-br18-5-56-mm-assault-rifle|archive-date=25 April 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Conventional Multirole Combat Rifle (CMCR)===\n{{Main|Conventional multirole combat rifle}}\n[[File:STK CMCR (12587721523).jpg|thumb|The Conventional Multirole Combat Rifle on display at the [[Singapore Airshow]] 2014]]\n\nThe 5.56mm Conventional Multirole Combat Rifle (CMCR) was released during the Singapore Airshow 2014.<ref name=\"ST Engineering\"/> Equipped with a unique adjustable and foldable buttstock, the CMCR provides ease and comfort for soldiers to manipulate in tight spaces. The CMCR is designed to fire NATO SS109 5.56mm ammunition and ST Kinetics' Extended Range 5.56mm ammunition, and come standard with MIL-STD-1913 Picatinny Rails at the three, six, nine and 12 o\u2019clock positions.<ref name=\"MilitaryTechnology\"/><ref>{{cite news|publisher= [[DefenseNews]] |title= ST Engineering Parades New Defense Products and Deals at Air Show\n|url= http://www.defensenews.com/article/20140211/DEFREG03/302110019/ST-Engineering-Parades-New-Defense-Products-Deals-Air-Show | year=2014}}</ref>\n\n===Compact Personal Weapon (CPW)===\n{{Main|ST Kinetics CPW}}\n\nThe CPW is a lightweight, multi-caliber [[Submachine Gun]] (SMG)/[[Personal Defense Weapon|Personal Defence Weapon]] (PDW) for [[Close Quarters Battle|Close Quarters Combat]] (CQB/CQC) operations as well as engagements up to 150m.\n\nThe CPW is available in [[9mm Parabellum]] (9\u00d719mm NATO) caliber for now and \"resembles an updated/modernized [[MP7A1]]\".<ref name = cpw>{{Cite web|url = http://www.defensereview.com/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=1188|title = ST Kinetics CPW (Compact Personal Weapon) Submachine Gun/PDW|publisher = Defense Review|author = David Crane}}</ref> The main differences are the angled pistol grip of the CPW for enhanced ergonomics and natural aiming, and a transparent rear magazine so that the operator can see the rounds remaining. Other features include a skeletonised trigger, a full-length [[Picatinny Rail|Mil-Std-1913 Picatinny top rail]] for mounting accessories such as optics and lasers, and a shorter bottom rail in front of the trigger guard for mounting a vertical foregrip.\n\nThe CPW weighs only 1.5&nbsp;kg empty/dry (2&nbsp;kg with a fully loaded 30-round 9&nbsp;mm magazine) and uses a unique bolt lever cam recoil mitigation system to control recoil and muzzle rise to increase target hits. Full-auto cyclic [[rate of fire]] is a relatively high 900 to 1100&nbsp;rpm.<ref name=brochure>{{Cite web |publisher= [[ST Engineering]] |access-date= 28 October 2008 |title= CPW Brochure |url= http://www.stengg.com/CoyCapPro/detail.aspx?pdid=399 |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20081209062121/http://www.stengg.com/CoyCapPro/detail.aspx?pdid=399 |archive-date= 9 December 2008 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===40 mm weapon and munition systems===\n{{Main|STK 40 AGL|STK 40 GL}}\n\nST Kinetics is one of the few producers of both 40&nbsp;mm munition and weapon systems.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= [[Defense News]] |title= Singapore Pushes To Dominate 40mm Grenade Market |url= http://www.defensenews.com/story.php?i=3379147 }}{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> The range of [[40 mm grenade|40&nbsp;mm rounds]] include low velocity, high velocity, less-than-lethal, camera,<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= [[ST Engineering]] |access-date= 11 September 2007 |title= 40mm SPARCS Product Brochure |url= http://www.stengg.com/upload/612TJKUY7dK8cTL7V66.pdf |format= PDF |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20060319220628/http://www.stengg.com/upload/612TJKUY7dK8cTL7V66.pdf |archive-date= 19 March 2006 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> self-destruct, airburst and enhanced blast insensitive explosive rounds. There are currently 3 weapon systems available, namely the 40&nbsp;mm Grenade Launcher (40GL), the 40&nbsp;mm Automatic Grenade Launcher (40AGL) and the 40&nbsp;mm Lightweight Automatic Grenade Launcher (40LWAGL, a portable version that is half the weight of conventional AGLs). The 40AGL was made in 1990, followed by the 40LWAGL in 2001 (previously called the 40&nbsp;mm Super Light Weight AGL). The 40AGL is mounted in combination with the 12.7-mm 50MG in the ST Kinetics' 40/50 cupola weapon system, installed on the M113 and Bionix. The 40AGL weighs 33&nbsp;kg without mount or ammunition. The objective of ST Kinetics in designing the 40LWAGL was to keep the grenade launcher's weight to below 20&nbsp;kg, or half the weight of conventional AGLs. Prototype weapons weighed around 14&nbsp;kg and small quantities have been sold to a few countries, including Sweden, mostly for evaluation. St Kinetics is also collaborating with Australia's [[Metal Storm Limited|Metal Storm]] and Electro Optics System to develop a new high-speed and recoilless 40&nbsp;mm grenade launcher called the Redback Lightweight.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Automatic+grenade+launchers:+new+automatic+40+mm+grenade+launchers...-a0171018007 | title=Automatic grenade launchers | publisher=Armada International | access-date=10 January 2008 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080520124918/http://www.thefreelibrary.com/Automatic+grenade+launchers%3a+new+automatic+40+mm+grenade+launchers...-a0171018007 | archive-date=20 May 2008 | url-status=live }}</ref> The company is reportedly the world's largest producer of the 40AGL, with more than 2,000 of the 40AGLs sold to the SAF and overseas customers.<ref>From bullet maker to defence tech giant, The Sunday Times, 30 December 2007, page 26</ref> In 2008, the company entered into a teaming agreement with [[Electro-Optic Systems]] (EOS) and [[Metal Storm Limited|Metal Storm]] (MS) to develop a 3-shot under-barrel grenade launcher called the [[Metal Storm Limited#3GL|3GL]].  The 3GL is intended to replace the M203 under barrel grenade launcher for most military rifles including the [[M16 rifle|M16]], [[AK-47]], [[SAR 21]] and [[Steyr AUG]].  It can also be detached to operate as a stand-alone weapon.<ref>{{cite news |publisher= [[Market Wire]] |title= Metal Storm Sets Weapons Commercialisation Path With ST Kinetics |url= http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_pwwi/is_/ai_n24330073 |year= 2008 |access-date= 15 December 2008 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20081212032131/http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_pwwi/is_/ai_n24330073 |archive-date= 12 December 2008 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nIn September 2013, Thales and ST Kinetics agreed to develop, manufacture and market ST Kinetics' 40mm low-velocity air-bursting ammunition for the Australian and New Zealand markets.<ref>{{cite news |publisher= [[IHS Jane's]] |title= DSEI 2013: Australian Munitions announces tie-ups with Diehl, ST Kinetics |url= http://www.janes.com/article/26947/dsei-2013-australian-munitions-announces-tie-ups-with-diehl-st-kinetics |year= 2013 |access-date= 6 December 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131210215731/http://www.janes.com/article/26947/dsei-2013-australian-munitions-announces-tie-ups-with-diehl-st-kinetics |archive-date= 10 December 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref> ST Kinetics also announced that the company secured a total of more than US$30 million worth of international orders from Canada and United States for its 40mm ammunition in October 2013.<ref>{{cite news |publisher= [[Land Warfare International]] |title= AUSA 2013: ST Kinetics secures ammo contracts |url= http://www.shephardmedia.com/news/landwarfareintl/ausa-2013-st-kinetics-secures-ammo-contracts/ |year= 2013 |access-date= 6 December 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131210105919/http://www.shephardmedia.com/news/landwarfareintl/ausa-2013-st-kinetics-secures-ammo-contracts/ |archive-date= 10 December 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===50MG machine gun===\n[[File:CIS 50 HMG.jpg|thumb|STK 50 HMG]]\n{{Main|STK 50MG}}\n\nThe 50MG was developed in the 1980s by CIS to replace the obsolete [[.50 BMG|{{Convert|12.7|mm|abbr=on}}]] [[M2 Browning|Browning M2HB machine guns]] used by the SAF. The CIS engineers learnt from the lesson of the unsuccessful American \"Dover Devil GPHMG\" programme, to create a modular weapon suited for modern tactical doctrines and production techniques. They succeeded and in 1988, CIS introduced the new machine gun and simply named it as the \"CIS 50MG\". The SAF used the 50MG in its infantry regiments and as a mounted weapon on armoured vehicles and naval craft. The STK 50MG is a gas-operated, air-cooled, belt-fed weapon. It has a quick-detachable barrel equipped with a carrying handle. The gun is operated using dual gas pistons, located in two gas tubes placed on either side of the barrel. The barrel is locked by means of a rotary bolt with multiple radial lugs that engages the barrel extension, eliminating the need for headspace adjustments. The STK 50MG utilizes the same \"constant recoil\" system used in the Ultimax 100. A unique feature of the 50MG is its dual belt-feed system that allows for fast and easy switching of ammunition from standard ball to armor-piercing [[Saboted light armor penetrator|Saboted Light Armor Penetrator (SLAP)]]. Such systems are more commonly used in modern automatic cannons.<ref name=\"JGRG2008-3\">Richard J (2008), page 398.</ref><ref name=\"JIDR1989-10\">Andrew C (October 1989).</ref><ref>{{Cite web|publisher=[[ST Engineering]]|access-date=12 April 2012|title=50MG Product Brochure|url=http://www.stengg.com/upload/1875jm6dmc40oAKikM8.pdf||url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090219082615/http://www.stengg.com/upload/1875jm6dmc40oAKikM8.pdf|archive-date=19 February 2009}}</ref>\n\n===120 mm Super Rapid Advanced Mortar System (SRAMS)===\nThe 120SRAMS is developed specifically for rapid and close range requirements of the battlefield. The semi-automatic Ammunition Transfer System and the patented Valve System in the breech mechanism provides an effective vent for the trapped air to let the bomb \"free-fall\" into the barrel. This reduces the projectile's in-bore travel and reportedly allows the 120SRAM to achieve the highest continuous firing rate of up to 18 rounds per minute\u20143 times faster than a conventional [[mortar (weapon)|mortar]] system which can fire up to 6 rounds per minute.<ref name= 120SRAM>{{Cite web |publisher= Defence Systems Daily |url= http://defence-data.com/dsei/pageds1019.htm |title= ST Kinetics unveil 120mm SRAMS and 40mm SLWAGL at DSEi |date= 12 September 2001 |access-date= 6 September 2007 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080202041757/http://defence-data.com/dsei/pageds1019.htm |archive-date= 2 February 2008 |url-status= live }}</ref> Recent product information has indicated the firing rate at a more modest 10 rounds per minute.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= ST Engineering |url= http://www.stengg.com/upload/620JKKP6Y94P4nl3aZf.pdf |format= PDF |title= 120SRAM Product Brochure |url-status= dead |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110717020329/http://www.stengg.com/upload/620JKKP6Y94P4nl3aZf.pdf |archive-date= 17 July 2011 |df= dmy-all }}</ref> The patented Cooling System is able to reduce the temperature that builds up in the barrel quickly to enable continuous firing without blockage. The patented Blast Diffuser reduces the blast overpressure by about 8 to 10 decibels. The 120SRAM is also currently the only system in the world with a recoil of less than 20 tonnes, which allows the 120SRAM to be mounted on board a 4\u00d74 wheeled vehicle. The 120SRAM has a navigation and positioning system, power gun drives and integrated with an automatic fire control system, which require just a 3-person crew to operate the weapon.<ref name= 120SRAM/>\n\n===FH-2000 field howitzer===\n{{Main|FH-2000}}\n\nThe FH-2000 is a 155&nbsp;mm 52-calibre towed [[howitzer]] gun and the \"first 52 calibre field howitzer in service and in series production\".<ref name= FAS>{{Cite web |url= http://www.fas.org/man/dod-101/sys/land/row/fh2000.htm |title= FH2000 |publisher= Federation of American Scientists |access-date= 7 January 2008 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20061015012456/http://www.fas.org/man/dod-101/sys/land/row/fh2000.htm |archive-date= 15 October 2006 |url-status= live }}</ref> Designed and built locally in Singapore by CIS, the FH-2000 deploys a crew of 8 and can use a low-powered self-propelled engine to travel at 10&nbsp;km/h without towing. It fires projectiles to a maximum range of 42&nbsp;km using special extended range ammunition that was field tested in New Zealand.\n\n===Pegasus 155mm lightweight howitzer===\n{{Main|SLWH Pegasus}}\n\nThe Pegasus is the world's first heli-portable 155&nbsp;mm 39 calibre self-propelled light howitzer, capable of offering aerial mobility for ''shoot and scoot''. The Pegasus' automatic ammunition loading system, advanced sight, lightweight material and innovative recoil management make the Pegasus highly survivable, fast to deploy and easy to use.\n\n===Primus self-propelled artillery===\n[[File:Primus 1.jpg|thumb|Primus on display]]\n{{Main|SSPH Primus}}\n\nThe Singapore Self-Propelled Howitzer 1 (SSPH 1) Primus is a [[self-propelled artillery]] unit armed with a 155&nbsp;mm [[howitzer]] jointly developed by the SAF, [http://www.dsta.gov.sg Defence Science and Technology Agency] (DSTA) and ST Kinetics. Primus provides the range, firepower and accuracy of the artillery while keeping its weight below 30 tons and width below 3m. Other self-propelled guns such as the U.S. ([[M109 Paladin]]), Britain's ([[AS-90|AS90 Braveheart]]), Japan's (Type 75) and Russia's (2S3M1) were either too heavy, at over 50 tons, or too wide, beyond 3m, for the tropical rainforest and swampy terrains. The chassis is based on the proven [[United Defense]] [[M109 Paladin|M109 155&nbsp;mm self-propelled howitzer]], with a new power pack similar to the one fitted on the [[Bionix AFV|Bionix infantry fighting vehicle]] (IFV). The power pack consists of a [[Detroit Diesel Corporation]] [[Series 92|6V 92TIA]] diesel engine developing 550&nbsp;hp coupled to a [[General Dynamics]] Land Systems HMPT-500-3EC fully automatic transmission. The maximum road speed of the Primus is 50&nbsp;km/h, with an operating range of 350&nbsp;km, its combat weight is of 28.3 tons allows it to use the SAF 's current military bridging systems. The Primus could be deployed by the future [[Airbus A400M]] Transport aircraft.\n\n===Bionix armoured fighting vehicle===\n{{Main|Bionix AFV}}\n\nThe Bionix was the first local [[armoured fighting vehicle]], designed and developed by ST Kinetics. It is a medium-weight tracked vehicle, weighing between twenty-two to twenty-eight tonnes, to replace the aging M-113A2 armoured personnel carriers. The Bionix was commissioned by the SAF in September 1997 and operated under the 42nd Battalion of the Singapore Armoured Regiment ([[42 SAR]]). During the commissioning parade in July 1999, then Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Defence, Dr Tony Tan, declared the Bionix IFV to be \"a highly effective indigenous armoured vehicle\".<ref>{{cite press release |publisher= Ministry of Defence, Singapore |title= SAF's First Infantry Fighting Vehicle Armoured Battle Group is Operational |date= 30 July 1999 |url= http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/news_and_events/nr/1999/jul/30jul99_nr.html |access-date= 31 December 2007 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20181215171823/http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/news_and_events/nr/1999/jul/30jul99_nr.html |archive-date= 15 December 2018 |url-status= live }}</ref> The Bionix was eventually succeeded by the Bionix II, which was jointly developed by the SAF, the Defence Science and Technology Agency (DSTA), and ST Kinetics.<ref>{{Cite web|publisher=[[Ministry of Defence (Singapore)]] |url=http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/mindef_websites/topics/Weapons/bx2/about.html |title=About Bionix II |date=30 November 2006 |access-date=6 September 2007 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071006092748/http://www.mindef.gov.sg/imindef/mindef_websites/topics/Weapons/bx2/about.html |archive-date=6 October 2007 |df= }}</ref>\n\n===Bronco all-terrain tracked carrier===\n{{Main|Bronco All Terrain Tracked Carrier}}\n\nThe Bronco is manufactured by ST Kinetics for the Singaporean Army and in small amounts as an UOR for the British Army in Afghanistan. The company is also manufacturing the firefighter and other civilian variants of the ATTC under its U.S. subsidiary, Hackney<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rescueleader.com/products/attv.htm|title=Hackney Emergency Vehicles|website=www.rescueleader.com|access-date=28 December 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080101040819/http://www.rescueleader.com/products/attv.htm|archive-date=1 January 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref> where it is positioned as a disaster recovery vehicle with its ability to access uneven and soft terrains impassable to normal vehicles after earthquakes, floods or other major urban catastrophes. Another commercial variant, the All Terrain Tracked Emergency-Engineering Car \u5168\u5730\u5f62\u5c65\u5e26\u5f0f\u5de5\u7a0b\u62a2\u9669,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.jonyang.com/2007/english/products/detail.asp?findid=12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080131231234/http://www.jonyang.com/2007/english/products/detail.asp?findid=12|url-status=dead|title=Product introduction-All terrain tracked emergencyengineering car-Products-Guizhou Jonyang Kinetics Co., Ltd|archive-date=31 January 2008}}</ref> is also under development by its China subsidiary, GJK, in a bid to leverage on China's cost advantage. Competition would include the Russian Vityaz DT-(10/20/30)P models<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cardatabase.net/search/search.php?manufacturer=Vityaz|title=Cardatabase.net \u2013 Car photo search \u2013 Vityaz|website=www.cardatabase.net|access-date=28 December 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080202005400/http://www.cardatabase.net/search/search.php?manufacturer=Vityaz|archive-date=2 February 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> and BAe Hagglunds' [[BVS10]].\n\n===Terrex AV81 8\u00d78 AFV===\n{{Main|Terrex}}\n\nThe Terrex AV81 is an [[armoured fighting vehicle]] weighing between 25 and 30 tons an 8\u00d78 wheeled chassis and modern armour. Multiple weapon platforms are supported, including both the remote and overhead weapons stations. The Terrex's modular design allows for different level of armour protection and weapon systems. It is designed to be air-portable by [[C-130]]s or equivalent cargo aircraft. The Terrex uses a patented independent [[double wishbone suspension]], which greatly improves ground mobility and comfort during rides over rough terrains. The use of automatic traction control and the capacity for large footprint off-road tyres enables the Terrex to reach high speed on soft ground. The vehicle has a double hull with an external [[V-hull]] that improves mine blast survivability. Add-on armour provides further protection for troops. It is also capable of providing full chemical, biological and nuclear protection in extreme operational conditions. The baseline configuration is fully [[Amphibious vehicle|amphibious]]. Two water jets mounted on either side at the back of the hull propel the vehicle through water at 10&nbsp;km/h. Initially developed for export sales from the number of emerging wheeled armoured vehicle requirements including U.S. [[Brigade combat team|Interim Brigade Combat Team]] (IBCT) concept, which calls for the need of wheeled armoured fighting vehicles (AFV) as opposed to tracked AFVs. In 2006, the SAF decided to purchase 135 units to replace their aging [[Cadillac Gage Commando|V-200]] armoured vehicles. The [[Indonesian Army]] also indicated plans to purchase 420 units and to produce the Terrex under license locally.<ref>{{Cite web |publisher= \u4e2d\u56fd\u56fd\u9632\u62a5 |url= http://jczs.sina.com.cn/2006-03-20/0942358456.html |title= \u65b0\u52a0\u5761\u7814\u5236\"\u7279\u62c9\u514b\u65af\"AV81\u88c5\u7532\u6b65\u6218\u8f66 |date= 20 March 2006 |access-date= 2 January 2008 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20060425042927/http://jczs.sina.com.cn/2006-03-20/0942358456.html |archive-date= 25 April 2006 |url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |publisher= Strategy Page |url= http://www.strategypage.com/dls/articles/Terrex-The-Terrific-9-22-2009.asp |title= Terrex the Terrific |date= 22 September 2009 |access-date= 15 November 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110616184300/http://www.strategypage.com/dls/articles/Terrex-The-Terrific-9-22-2009.asp |archive-date= 16 June 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\n===Hunter armoured fighting vehicle===\n{{Main|Hunter AFV}}\n\nThe Hunter was jointly developed with [[Defence Science and Technology Agency]], and the [[Singapore Army]]. Intended to replace the Singapore Army's aging Ultra [[M113 Armored Personnel Carrier|M113]] [[armoured personnel carrier]]s, it was commissioned in 2019. It is the Singapore Army's first fully digitalised platform and is designed to provide armoured forces with enhanced capabilities to operate more effectively and efficiently in various phases of military operations.\n\n===Other military and para-military products===\n;Munitions\n*81&nbsp;mm [[Mortar (weapon)|Mortar]]\n*120&nbsp;mm Mortar\n*155&nbsp;mm Large Calibre Munition\n*[[Hand grenade]]s\n*[[Pyrotechnics]]\n\n;Small arms\n*7.62&nbsp;mm [[General Purpose Machine Gun]] (GPMG)\n\n;Platform\n[[File:Singapore Army Mark 2 Light Strike Vehicle on display at the National Museum of Singapore - 20140223.jpg|thumb|right|Spider New Generation Light Strike Vehicle]]\n*[[Light Strike Vehicle (Singapore)|Spider New Generation (New Gen)]] Light Strike Vehicle (LSV)\n*Light Armoured Multi-Role Vehicle (LAMV)\n*Mini All Terrain Vehicle (MATV)\n*Asset Maintenance\n*[[Contract Manufacturing]]\n\n;[[Homeland Security]] Solutions\n*Rapid Deployment Solution\n*Security Tamper Evident Bags (STEB)\n*Demul X Biological & Chemical Decontamination System (BCDS)\n*Integrated Mail Screening System (IMSS)\n*Demilitarisation services (Demil)\n*Analysis, Test and Evaluation (AT&E)\n*Advanced Logistics Proactive Solutions (ALPS)\n\n==Commercial equipment==\nST Kinetics started on the commercial vehicle business in 2004 and has yet to establish a presence in the global marketplace even though its subsidiaries are well-established brands within their respective countries. In 2008, ST Kinetics began to market selected commercial vehicles and the hybrid drive solutions as ecological products.\n\n===Construction vehicles===\nST Kinetics' BZK JV in China produces fixed and articulated off-road dumptrucks ranging from 20 to 52 ton. BZK also produces complementary products like cement carriers and mixers and [[Shunt truck|terminal port tractors]] for container ports operation. Jonyang excavators has been in operation in China and surrounding regions over 30 years, and manufactured both wheeled and tracked hydraulic excavators. LeeBoy has been a leading producer of commercial asphalt pavers and motor-graders since 1964 in the U.S.\n\n===Distribution vehicles===\nHackney and Kidron are aluminium and refrigerated truck bodies manufacturers respectively in the U.S. Hackney beverage trucks has been marketing its optimised compartmentalisation and light-weight aluminium bodies as means to lower lifecycle costs to the operators. Kidron has pioneered multi-temperature distribution with its Adjustable Compartmentalised Multi-temperature System (ACMT) of movable partitions. The ACMT allows configuration of loads requiring different temperature and compartment sizes.\n\n===Urban and emergency vehicles===\nHackney Emergency also designs emergency vehicles for the U.S. markets such as firetrucks and HAZMAT vehicles.  ST Kinetics itself also produces a series of urban vehicles, such as [[ambulance]]s, [[HAZMAT]] vehicles, [[fire engines]], terminal prime movers for local use, mostly for local use by the [[Singapore Civil Defence Force]] and the [[Singapore Police Force]].\n\nIn addition, ST Kinetics is the sole importer and distributor of [[MAN Truck & Bus]] vehicles within Singapore.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stengg.com/en/products-solutions/man-truck-and-bus|title=ST Engineering \u2013 MAN Truck and Bus|access-date=9 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190709020603/https://www.stengg.com/en/products-solutions/man-truck-and-bus|archive-date=9 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Automotive services==\nThe automotive services have continued since the SAE days to become the Total Support & Services arm of the present day ST Kinetics. ST Kinetics continue to provide MRO services to military, commercial and general customers.\n\n===MRO services for military vehicles===\nAs part of the integrated logistics support system for the major platforms, ST Kinetics has established the MRO services under its Kinetics Integrated Services (KIS) arm. KIS also provides maintenance of the existing SAF fleet of MAN trucks.\n\n===Component servicing===\nSDDA is both Detroit Diesel and Allison transmission's Asia distribution centre as well as a service hub for the overhaul of automotive engines, Allison transmissions and fuel injection pumps, and the servicing of electrical, electronic, hydraulic & mechanical components.\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Bibliography\n{{Refbegin}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Richard Jones|last2=Andrew White|title=Jane's Guns Recognition Guide|year=2008|publisher=[[HarperCollins]]|isbn=978-0-00-726645-6}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Andrew|first=C Tillman|date=August 1989|title=IDR test report: Ultimax light machine gun&nbsp;\u2014 the ultimate in controllability|journal=[[Jane's International Defence Review]]|pages=1093\u20131095|issn=0020-6512}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Andrew|first=C Tillman|date=October 1989|title=IDR test report: Singapore's Lightweight Heavy|journal=Jane's International Defence Review|pages=1377\u20131380|issn=0020-6512|url=http://i295.photobucket.com/albums/mm137/spyder-album2/Singapore/CIS-50MG-2.jpg|accessdate=12 April 2012}}\n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.stengg.com/en/land-systems/ ST Engineering Land Systems official website]\n\n{{Singapore-designed weapons}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:St Kinetics}}\n[[Category:Defence companies]]\n[[Category:Engineering companies of Singapore]]\n[[Category:Military vehicle manufacturers]]\n", "name_user": "Datinterestedboi", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eSAR 21 5.56 assault rifle", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ST_Kinetics"}
{"title_page": "Chauncey Billups", "text_new": "{{short description|American basketball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox basketball biography\n| image = Chauncey Billups Nuggets.jpg\n| caption = Billups with the Denver Nuggets in 2011\n| name = Chauncey Billups\n| position = \n| height_ft = 6\n| height_in = 3\n| weight_lb = 200\n| league = \n| team =\n| nationality = American\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1976|9|25}}\n| birth_place = [[Denver|Denver, Colorado]]\n| high_school = [[George Washington High School (Colorado)|George Washington]]<br>(Denver, Colorado)\n| college = [[Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball|Colorado]] (1995\u20131997)\n| draft_year = 1997\n| draft_round = 1\n| draft_pick = 3\n| draft_team = [[Boston Celtics]]\n| career_position = [[Point guard]] / [[Shooting guard]]\n| career_number = 4, 3, 1, 7\n| career_start = 1997\n| career_end = 2014\n| years1 ={{nbay|1997|full=y}} | team1 = [[Boston Celtics]]\n| years2 ={{nbay|1997|end}}\u2013{{nbay|1998|end}} | team2 = [[Toronto Raptors]]\n| years3 ={{nbay|1998|end}}\u2013{{nbay|1999|end}} | team3 = [[Denver Nuggets]]\n| years4 ={{nbay|2000|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2001|end}} | team4 = [[Minnesota Timberwolves]]\n| years5 ={{nbay|2002|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2008|start}} | team5 = [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| years6 ={{nbay|2008|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2010|end}} | team6 = Denver Nuggets\n| years7 ={{nbay|2010|end}} | team7 =[[New York Knicks]]\n| years8 ={{nbay|2011|start}}\u2013{{nbay|2012|end}} |team8=[[Los Angeles Clippers]]\n| years9 ={{nbay|2013|full=y}} | team9 = Detroit Pistons\n| highlights =\n* [[NBA champion]] ([[2004 NBA Finals|2004]])\n* [[Bill Russell NBA Finals Most Valuable Player Award|NBA Finals MVP]] ([[2004 NBA Finals|2004]])\n* 5\u00d7 [[NBA All-Star]] ([[2006 NBA All-Star Game|2006]]\u2013[[2010 NBA All-Star Game|2010]])\n* [[All-NBA Second Team]] ({{nbay|2005|end}})\n* 2\u00d7 [[All-NBA Third Team]] ({{nbay|2006|end}}, {{nbay|2008|end}})\n* 2\u00d7 [[NBA All-Defensive Second Team]] ({{nbay|2004|end}}, {{nbay|2005|end}})\n* [[J. Walter Kennedy Citizenship Award]] ({{nbay|2007|end}})\n* [[NBA Sportsmanship Award]] ({{nbay|2008|end}})\n* [[Twyman\u2013Stokes Teammate of the Year Award|NBA Teammate of the Year]] ({{nbay|2012|end}})\n* No. 1 [[Detroit Pistons#Retired numbers|retired by Detroit Pistons]]\n* Consensus second-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] ([[1997 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1997]])\n* No. 4 [[Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball#Retired jerseys|retired by Colorado Buffaloes]]\n* Second-team [[Parade All-America Boys Basketball Team|''Parade'' All-American]] (1995)\n* Fourth-team ''Parade'' All-American (1994)\n* 3\u00d7 [[Mr. Colorado Basketball]] (1993\u20131995)\n| stat1label = [[Point (basketball)|Points]]\n| stat1value = 15,802 (15.2 ppg)\n| stat2label = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]]\n| stat2value = 2,992 (2.9 rpg)\n| stat3label = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]]\n| stat3value = 5,636 (5.4 apg)\n| bbr = billuch01\n| nba_profile = chauncey_billups\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalCountry|{{flagu|United States}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA Americas Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2007 FIBA Americas Championship|2007 Las Vegas]] | [[2007 FIBA Americas Championship|Team Competition]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIBA World Championship]]}}\n{{MedalGold| [[2010 FIBA World Championship|2010 Turkey]] | [[2010 United States men's FIBA World Championship team|Team competition]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Chauncey Ray Billups''' (born September 25, 1976) is an American former professional [[basketball]] player.  He played 17 seasons in the [[National Basketball Association]] (NBA). After playing [[college basketball]] with the [[Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball|Colorado Buffaloes]], he was selected third overall in the [[1997 NBA draft]] by the [[Boston Celtics]]. A five-time [[NBA All-Star]] and a three-time All-NBA selection, Billups played for the Celtics, [[Toronto Raptors]], [[Denver Nuggets]], [[Minnesota Timberwolves]], [[Detroit Pistons]], [[New York Knicks]], and [[Los Angeles Clippers]] during his NBA career. He won the [[NBA Finals MVP]] in 2004 after helping the Pistons beat the [[Los Angeles Lakers]] in the [[2004 NBA Finals|Finals]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/2008/writers/steve_aschburner/11/03/billups/|title=Back home after trade, Billups has something to prove with Nuggets|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=November 3, 2008|first=Steve|last=Aschburner}}</ref> and was given the nickname \"'''Mr. Big Shot'''\" for making late-game shots with Detroit.<ref name=\"OTL\">{{cite news|url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/eticket/story?page=090511/billups|title=The Disposable Superstar|publisher=ESPN.com|work=[[Outside the Lines]]|date=May 11, 2009|first=Tom|last=Friend}}</ref> The Pistons [[retired number|retired]] his No. 1 jersey in 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Billups: 'I just wanted to be a champion'|url = http://www.detroitnews.com/story/sports/nba/pistons/2016/02/10/jersey-retirement-emotional-experience-billups/80208150/|website = Detroit News|access-date = February 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, Colorado retired his No. 4. The [[Coors Events Center]] also has a large mural of Billups in the northeast corner of the arena as part of his \"Chauncey's Kid Roundup\" program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buffzone.com/ci_17487925|title=One Chauncey Billups mural replaced at CU|publisher=|accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\n==High school career==\nBorn in [[Denver]], [[Colorado]],<ref name=\"Curr Bio\">{{cite book|title=Current Biography Yearbook 2011|year=2011|publisher=H.W. Wilson|location=Ipswich, Massachusetts|isbn=9780824211219|pages=[https://archive.org/details/currentbiography0000unse_z0h6/page/67 67\u201370]|chapter=Billups, Chauncey|url=https://archive.org/details/currentbiography0000unse_z0h6/page/67}}</ref> Billups graduated from [[George Washington High School (Denver)|George Washington High School]] of Denver in 1995. At George Washington, he was a four-time All-State first team pick, Colorado Mr. Basketball three times, and Colorado Player of the Year as a sophomore and as a junior. He started on varsity as a freshman. He was selected to the 1995 [[McDonald's All-American Team]] but did not play due to a shoulder injury.\n\n==College career==\nFor college, Billups chose the [[University of Colorado Boulder]] over Kansas, Georgia Tech, University of California-Berkeley, and Oklahoma State. He averaged 18.5 points, 5.1 assists, and 5.6 rebounds per game over his two seasons with the [[Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball|Buffaloes]]. In the 1996\u201397 season, he was named to the All-[[Big 12 Conference]] First Team, the Basketball Times All-American First Team, and Consensus 2nd team All-American. That same season, Colorado finished second in the Big 12 conference with an overall record of 22\u201310. Billups then led the Buffaloes to their first NCAA tournament appearance in 28 years. As a 9-seed, Billups and the Buffalos upset the 8-seed Indiana Hoosiers 80\u201362 but then lost to the North Carolina Tar Heels 56\u201373. Billups averaged 17.5 points, 5.5 rebounds, and 3.0 assists per game.<ref>{{Cite web|title = 1997 Colorado Buffaloes|url = https://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/colorado/1997.html|website = College Basketball at Sports-Reference.com|access-date = February 20, 2016|url-status = dead|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20160216175404/http://www.sports-reference.com/cbb/schools/colorado/1997.html|archivedate = February 16, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===College Awards & Honors===\n* Consensus second-team [[NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|All-American]] ([[1997 NCAA Men's Basketball All-Americans|1997]])\n* All-[[Big 12 Conference|Big 12]] First Team (1997)\n* AllBuffs.com [[Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball#The AllBuffs.com All-Time Men's Basketball Team|All-Time Colorado Buffaloes Men's Basketball Team]]\n* No. 4 retired by [[Colorado Buffaloes men's basketball#Retired jerseys|University of Colorado]]\n\n==NBA career==\n\n=== Boston Celtics (1997\u20131998) ===\nBillups was drafted third overall in the [[1997 NBA draft]] by the [[1997\u201398 Boston Celtics season|Boston Celtics]]. He did not mesh with new Celtics head coach [[Rick Pitino]]. In his first career game, Billups recorded 15 points, 2 rebounds and 4 assists in 16 minutes of playing time as a reserve in a win against the Michael Jordan-led [[1997-98 Chicago Bulls season|Bulls]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/boxscores/199710310BOS.html|title=Chicago Bulls at Boston Celtics Box Score, October 31, 1997|publisher=Basketball-Reference|accessdate=September 13, 2019}}</ref> In his eighth career game, Billups posted a then career-high 22 points, on 5-for-14 shooting from the field and 9-for-10 from the free throw line, to go along with 3 assists and 4 steals, in a 103-99 win over the visiting [[1997-98 Toronto Raptors season|Raptors]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/boxscores/199711140BOS.html|title=Toronto Raptors at Boston Celtics Box Score, November 14, 1997|publisher=Basketball-Reference|accessdate=September 13, 2019}}</ref> Years later, Billups reflected on his stint in Boston, commenting, \"That didn't help. That didn't give me a chance to really slow down and listen to myself, listen to the game and what's going on. I never really had that chance. It was a recipe for disaster there.\" In addition, the Celtics coaching staff did not know whether to play him as a [[point guard]] or [[shooting guard]]. Fifty-one games later, Billups was traded to the [[1997\u201398 Toronto Raptors season|Toronto Raptors]] on the trading deadline.<ref name=\"theplayerstribune.com\">{{Cite web|title = Letter to My Younger Self {{!}} By Chauncey Billups|url = http://www.theplayerstribune.com/chauncey-billups-nba-letter-to-my-younger-self/|website = The Players' Tribune|access-date = February 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Toronto Raptors (1998\u201399)===\nOn February 18, 1998, Billups was traded to the [[1997\u201398 Toronto Raptors season|Toronto Raptors]], along with [[Roy Rogers (basketball)|Roy Rogers]], [[Dee Brown (basketball, born 1968)|Dee Brown]], and [[John Thomas (basketball)|John Thomas]] in exchange for All-Star point guard [[Kenny Anderson (basketball)|Kenny Anderson]], [[\u017dan Tabak]], and [[Popeye Jones]].<ref name=\"theplayerstribune.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|first=Steven|last=Loung|title=The 6 most impactful trade deadlines in Toronto Raptors history|url=https://www.sportsnet.ca/basketball/nba/6-impactful-trade-deadlines-toronto-raptors-history/|website=Sportsnet|date=February 5, 2019|accessdate=March 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Wise|first=Mike|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/02/19/sports/basketball-kenny-anderson-is-traded-to-celtics-in-7-player-deal.html|title=Kenny Anderson, Chauncey Billups, involved in a 7-player deal|publisher=The New York Times|date=February 19, 1998|accessdate=September 18, 2019}}</ref> On February 22, in just his second career game with the Raptors, Billups recorded a then-career high of 27 points on 5-for-13 shooting from the field and 13-for-16 from the free throw line, to go along with 2 rebounds and 5 assists in a 113-105 win over the [[1997-98 Vancouver Grizzlies season|Vancouver Grizzlies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/boxscores/199802220TOR.html|title=Vancouver Grizzlies at Toronto Raptors Box Score, February 22, 1998|publisher=Basketball-Reference|accessdate=September 18, 2019}}</ref> On March 3, Billups recorded 26 points to go along with 5 rebounds and 6 assists in a 93-108 loss to the visiting [[1997-98 Utah Jazz season|Utah Jazz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/boxscores/199803030TOR.html|title=Utah Jazz at Toronto Raptors Box Score, March 3, 1998|publisher=Basketball-Reference|accessdate=September 18, 2019}}</ref> On April 14, Billups recorded 19 points, 6 rebounds and 4 assists in a 96-92 road win over the New Jersey Nets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/boxscores/199804140NJN.html|title=Toronto Raptors at New Jersey Nets Box Score, April 14, 1998|publisher=Basketball-Reference|accessdate=October 13, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 21, 1999, he was dealt to his hometown [[1998\u201399 Denver Nuggets season|Denver Nuggets]] in a three-way deal involving one of Billups's future teams, the [[1998\u201399 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Minnesota Timberwolves]].\n\n=== Denver Nuggets (1999\u20132000) ===\nMinnesota received [[Dean Garrett]] and [[Bobby Jackson (basketball)|Bobby Jackson]] from Denver, Toronto received [[\u017deljko Rebra\u010da]] and [[Micheal Williams]] from Minnesota and the 5th pick in the [[1999 NBA draft]] from Denver. Billups, along with [[Tyson Wheeler]], was sent to Denver from Toronto. Three months into his first tenure with the Nuggets, Billups visited a local Denver hospital in order to comfort and inspire Patrick Ireland, a victim of the 1999 [[Columbine High School massacre|Columbine High School Shooting Massacre]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/espn/otl/news/story?id=4069745|title=Ten years after: A Columbine survivor's story|date=April 15, 2009|publisher=|accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref> A year later, on February 1, 2000, Billups was traded to the [[1999\u20132000 Orlando Magic season|Orlando Magic]] along with [[Ron Mercer]] and [[Johnny Taylor (basketball)|Johnny Taylor]] in exchange for [[Chris Gatling]], [[Tariq Abdul-Wahad]], a future first-round pick, and cash.<ref name=Schmitz>{{cite web|first=Brian|last=Schmitz|title=Letting Chauncey Billups go haunted Orlando Magic for years|url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/2010-01-13/sports/os-orlando-magic-what-if-chauncy-billups-20100113_1_jameer-nelson-magic-fans-chauncey-billups|website=Orlando Sentinel|date=January 13, 2010|accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|first=Mark|last=Shapiro|title= NUGGETS SHIP MERCER TO MAGIC|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-2000-02-02-0002020098-story.html|website=Chicago Tribune|date=February 2, 2000|accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Orlando Magic (2000)===\nBillups was on the injured list until season's end due to an injured shoulder and never played a game for the Magic.<ref name=Schmitz/> Despite this, he was included in the season-ending team photo.<ref>{{cite web|title=Season-by-Season Magic Team Photos|url=https://www.nba.com/magic/galleries/season-by-season-magic-team-photos-20180320|website=Orlando Magic|date=March 20, 2018|accessdate=January 10, 2019}}</ref> Among NBA circles, Billups was considered a draft bust.<ref name=Schmitz/>\n\n=== Minnesota Timberwolves (2000\u20132002)===\nBillups was signed by the [[2000\u201301 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Minnesota Timberwolves]] (who had been involved in the trade that sent Billups to Denver) as a back-up to then point guard [[Terrell Brandon]], who would mentor the troubled player alongside [[Sam Mitchell (basketball)|Sam Mitchell]], [[Wally Sczerbiak]], and [[Kevin Garnett]].<ref name=\"OTL\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Timberwolves Sign Billups, Smith|url=https://apnews.com/8675f20d3fad8185284f4b9ceeb40e74|website=Associated Press|date=August 8, 2000|accessdate=March 15, 2019}}</ref> Billups would work with his more experienced teammates on shooting, scouting, decision-making and the other attributes that came with playing point guard in the NBA, such as learning to work more effectively with teammates, and deciding which plays would be most beneficial for the team in a specific situation.<ref name=\"theplayerstribune.com\"/>\n\nIn his first career game with the [[2000-01 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Timberwolves]], Billups recorded 15 points, 2 rebounds and 5 assists in a 106-98 road win over the Houston Rockets.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/boxscores/200010310HOU.html|title=Minnesota Timberwolves at Houston Rockets Box Score, October 31, 2000|publisher=Basketball-Reference|accessdate=October 17, 2019}}</ref> On November 11, 2000, Billups recorded his season-high in terms of points scored with 31 points to go along with 5 rebounds and 9 assists in a 103-92 road win over the [[2000-01 Milwaukee Bucks season|Bucks]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/boxscores/200011110MIL.html|title=Minnesota Timberwolves at Milwaukee Bucks Box Score, November 11, 2000|publisher=Basketball-Reference|accessdate=October 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 2001\u201302 season, Brandon suffered a serious knee injury. Billups replaced him and had a breakthrough 2001\u201302 season. The Timberwolves won 50 games before they were swept by the [[2001\u201302 Dallas Mavericks season|Dallas Mavericks]] in the first round of the playoffs, with Billups averaging 22 points per game in the series.<ref name=\"OTL\"/>\n\n===Detroit Pistons (2002\u20132008)===\n[[File:ChaunceyBillups.jpg|thumb|right|175px|Billups with the Pistons in 2005]]\nAfter his breakthrough season, Billups became a [[free agent]]. Billups wanted to return to the Timberwolves, but the team wanted to see how Brandon would respond to his knee injury.<ref name=\"OTL\"/>\n\nIn June 2002, Billups signed a 5-year, $35 million contract with the [[2002\u201303 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit Pistons]] to be the team's new starting [[point guard]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/pistons/news/billupssign_020717.html|title=Pistons Sign Free Agent Guard Chauncey Billups|work=Pistons.com|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc|accessdate=May 20, 2009|date=July 17, 2002}}</ref> When he signed with the Pistons, he was forced to take the number 1 because number 4 was retired in honor of [[Joe Dumars]]. Billups quickly earned respect from Pistons fans and colleagues for his tenacious defense and clutch shooting.\n\nIn 2002\u201303, Billups helped Detroit finish first overall in the Eastern Conference with a 50\u201332 regular season record. Billups earned the nickname \"Mr. Big-Shot\" during the regular season for two events. He first made a game winning three on March 9 as time expired to beat the Golden State Warriors 107\u2013105 and Billups scored 31 points. The second event was just over two weeks later on March 26. The Pistons were tied in overtime with the Atlanta Hawks 99\u201399 until Billups made a top-of-the-key triple with 0.5 seconds left to win the game. Billups finished with 22 points against the Hawks. In the 2003 Playoffs, the top-seed Pistons surprisingly fell behind the upstart 8-seed Orlando Magic in the first round series 3 games to 1. In game 5, Billups played a contributing role in his team's dominating 98\u201367 victory by scoring 15 points, tied for second on the Pistons. Having helped the Pistons stave off elimination in Game 5, Billups scored 40 points in game 6 to help the Pistons force a seventh game. In the decisive Game 7, Billups scored 37 points to help clinch the series 4\u20133.\n\nDetroit then beat the [[2002-03 Philadelphia 76ers season|Philadelphia 76ers]] in the Eastern Conference Semi-Finals, 4\u20132, to advance to the Eastern Conference Finals. However, Detroit would be swept by the [[2002-03 New Jersey Nets season|New Jersey Nets]], 4\u20130. [[Rick Carlisle]] was fired as the head coach in the offseason and [[Larry Brown (basketball)|Larry Brown]] was hired.\n\nIn the 2004 season, Billups averaged 16.9 points, 5.7 assists, 3.5 rebounds, and 1.1 steals per game. The Pistons improved their record to 54\u201328, but it was only good for the third seed overall in the Eastern Conference playoff standings.\n\n[[File:ChaunceyBillupsWizards.jpg|thumb|194px|left|Billups in 2008]]\nIn the pivotal Game 3 during the first round series against the Milwaukee Bucks, which was tied 1-1, Billups led all scorers with 21 points and finished the scoring for his team by sinking 4 of 4 free throws in the final 31.2 seconds. These free throws were a key part of the Pistons effort to stave off the Bucks' relentless defense which kept Detroit from scoring a normal field goal during the last 5:34.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20040424/DETMIL/recap.html|title=NBA.com: Pistons Giveth, Taketh Away|publisher=|accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref> In the Eastern Conference Semifinals versus the defending Eastern Conference Champions the New Jersey Nets, Billups banked in a half-court three as time expired in game 5 to send the game into overtime. The Pistons would lose in triple overtime. Finally, he helped Detroit overcome a 3\u20132 series deficit to win the series, 4\u20133.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/games/20040520/NJNDET/recap.html|title=NBA.com: Pistons Pulverize Nets, Advance to East Finals|publisher=|accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn the Eastern Conference Finals against the Indiana Pacers, the Pistons won the gritty, defensive series, 4\u20132, by an average score of 75.2 PPG to the Pacers' 72.7 PPG.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/boxscores/200303090DET.html|title=Golden State Warriors at Detroit Pistons Box Score, March 9, 2003 - Basketball-Reference.com|publisher=|accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe helped Detroit win the [[2004 NBA Finals]] over the heavily favored [[2003\u201304 Los Angeles Lakers season|Los Angeles Lakers]], 4\u20131. He averaged per game 21 points, 5.2 assists, 3.2 RPG, 1.2 SPG, as well as shooting 50.1% FG, 47.1% 3PT, and 92.9% FT to earn the [[NBA Finals MVP Award]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.basketball-reference.com/playoffs/2004-nba-finals-pistons-vs-lakers.html|title=2004 NBA Finals - Basketball-Reference.com|publisher=|accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref> Billups said of his MVP award, \"Everybody deserves this. Not just me. I wish I could turn it into thirteen pieces and give a little bit to everybody.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=4DHamPfSTNY|title=Detroit Pistons - Glory Times, 2004 Championship|publisher=|accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe following season, Billups was named to the 2005 NBA Second All-Defensive Team, along with teammate [[Tayshaun Prince]], while teammate and co-captain of the Pistons [[Ben Wallace]] took home the Defensive Player of the Year Award. The Pistons reached the [[2005 NBA Finals]] but lost in their bid to repeat as champions to the [[2004\u201305 San Antonio Spurs season|San Antonio Spurs]] in seven games.\n\nIn 2006, Billups was co-captain of the team. Although he captained the Pistons to a franchise best 64\u201318 record, they failed to make it to the NBA Finals for the first time in three years.\n\nOn July 11, 2007, Billups signed a $46 million, four-year contract with the Pistons (which includes a team option for a fifth year at $14 million).<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/nba/news/story?id=2932809 ESPN \u2013 Pistons keep Billups with four-year, $46M deal \u2013 NBA]. Sports.espn.go.com (July 11, 2007). Retrieved on 2012-05-27.</ref> He had been an [[unrestricted free agent]] for several days after he opted out of the previous contract, which he had signed in 2002.\n\nIn the first round of the 2008 NBA playoffs, during Game 3 against the Orlando Magic, Billups injured his right hamstring when Orlando Magic guard [[Jameer Nelson]] tangled with Billup's left leg on a drive to the bucket. Billups would sit for the 3 remaining games of the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=r3xgeosSvb4|title=Game 3 Round 2 Orlando vs Detroit Pistons 2008 NBA playoffs|first=|last=the2008playoffsblitz|date=May 16, 2008|publisher=|accessdate=March 1, 2017|via=YouTube}}</ref> Billups and the Pistons again made it to the Eastern Conference Finals against the Celtics, but lost the series, 4\u20132, to the eventual champions.\n\n===Return to Denver Nuggets (2008\u20132011)===\n[[File:Chauncey Billups.jpg|thumb|175px|right|Billups with the Denver Nuggets]]\nOn November 3, 2008, Billups was traded to the [[2008\u201309 Denver Nuggets season|Denver Nuggets]], along with [[Antonio McDyess]] and [[Cheikh Samb]], for [[Allen Iverson]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.denverpost.com/sports/ci_10887199 | work=Denver Post | first=Benjamin | last=Hochman | title=Nuggets ship Iverson to Detroit for Billups | date=November 3, 2008}}</ref> Pistons GM [[Joe Dumars]] said that it was \"the hardest and toughest\" move he had made as a general manager, describing Billups as \"... a guy that I have looked at as a little brother.\"\n\nBillups chose the #7 jersey to honor [[Denver Broncos]] [[quarterback]] [[John Elway]], since two of his other favorite numbers, 1 and 4, were already worn by [[J. R. Smith]] and [[Kenyon Martin]], respectively.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ap.google.com/article/ALeqM5g9vNaZwDoXeGaCeFyJXmTKM8papAD949PTPG4|title=No place like home for Denver native Billups|agency=Associated Press|first=Pat|last=Graham|date=November 7, 2008}}{{dead link|date=August 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> He played his first game of the Nuggets' [[2008\u201309 Denver Nuggets season|2008\u201309 season]] on November 7, 2008. He recorded 15 points, four rebounds and three assists in 30 minutes of play in a 108\u2013105 Nuggets' home win.<ref>[http://scores.espn.go.com/nba/recap?gameId=281107007 Dallas Mavericks vs. Denver Nuggets \u2013 Recap \u2013 November 07, 2008 \u2013 ESPN]. Scores.espn.go.com (November 7, 2008). Retrieved on 2012-05-27.</ref> He finished the season averaging 17.7 points, and 6.4 assists per game.\n\nWith Billups and [[Carmelo Anthony]], the Nuggets accomplished a number of franchise milestones. Their 54\u201328 record matched a franchise record, and their 27\u201314 start was also a franchise record for wins in the first half of a season. This also marked the first time in the franchise's history the team had gotten 50 wins in back-to-back seasons. They led the Northwest division for much of the season, eventually winning the division and gaining the number two seed in the Western Conference, matching the highest the team had ever been seeded for the playoffs. In the first round, they defeated the [[2007\u201308 New Orleans Hornets season|New Orleans Hornets]] in 5 games, which included a record-equaling 58-point margin-of-victory. Billups also set a Nuggets franchise record with the most 3 pointers in a playoff game with 8, and his 19 3-pointers in total is also a Nuggets record for threes made in a playoff series. In his first year with the Nuggets, Billups led them back to the [[NBA Conference Finals]] for the first time since 1985. They would play the Lakers for the second straight year (the Lakers had swept them in the first round the year before). The Nuggets would ultimately lose the series 4-2. This was Billups' 7th straight conference finals. He joined [[Magic Johnson]], [[Michael Cooper]], [[Kareem Abdul-Jabbar]], and [[Kurt Rambis]] as the only players to accomplish this feat since the [[Boston Celtics]] of the 1950s and 1960s led by [[Bill Russell]]. Billups finished the season sixth in voting for the 2009 [[NBA Most Valuable Player Award]]. He was also selected to his second [[All-NBA Third Team]].\n\nFor the [[2009\u201310 NBA season|2009\u201310 season]], Billups reverted to wearing #1, the same number he wore with the Pistons. Teammate J. R. Smith, who had previously worn #1 since being acquired by the Nuggets in 2006, changed to the #5 jersey.<ref>[http://www.nba.com/nuggets/roster Denver Nuggets official website]. NBA.com. Retrieved on May 27, 2012.</ref> On November 27, 2009, in the Nuggets' 128\u2013125 win over the [[2009\u201310 New York Knicks season|New York Knicks]], Billups scored 32 points while teammate Carmelo Anthony scored 50. This made them only the third duo in NBA history to score at least 30 and 50 points respectively. On February 5, 2010, Billups set a career high in points with a 39-point performance in a road win over the [[2009\u201310 Los Angeles Lakers season|Los Angeles Lakers]] with 27 of them coming from 9 three-pointers. During the 2010\u201311 season, he averaged 16.5 points per game, 5.3 assists per game, and 2.5 rebounds per game in 32.3 minutes per game. His .441 three point field goal percentage was a career high.\n\n===New York Knicks (2011)===\nDespite publicly professing his desire to finish his career in hometown Denver and retire as a member of the Nuggets, Billups was traded to the [[2010\u201311 New York Knicks season|New York Knicks]] on February 22, 2011<ref>{{cite web | title = Knicks Acquire Four-Time All-Star Carmelo Anthony | url = http://www.nba.com/knicks/news/carmeloanthonyacquired.html | work = [[NBA.com]] | date = February 22, 2011 | accessdate = February 23, 2011}}</ref> as part of the [[Carmelo Anthony]] deal. Billups was \"collateral damage\"\u2014as more than one sportswriter put it\u2014of Carmelo Anthony's desire to play in New York and the Nuggets' desire to trade Anthony before he became a free agent.<ref>[http://sports.espn.go.com/new-york/nba/news/story?id=6145912 Sources: New York Knicks complete deal for Carmelo Anthony \u2013 ESPN New York]. Sports.espn.go.com (February 22, 2011). Retrieved on 2012-05-27.</ref> \"Oh it was hard, hardest thing I've ever had to do\", Billups said. \"I had to tell my girls that daddy was traded, that he was leaving to play across the country. I told them it wasn't my choice, that nothing could be done about it. I had to go. It wasn't a happy scene.\"<ref>{{cite web | title = Carmelo Tends to Garden of Good and Evil | url = http://lisa-olson.fanhouse.com/2011/02/24/carmelo-anthony-the-orchestrator-of-the-garden-of-good-and-evil/ | work = [[FanHouse]] | date = February 24, 2011 | accessdate = February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe Knicks finished 42\u201340 and clinched the sixth seed in the Eastern Conference and made the playoffs for the first time since 2004. Billups suffered a knee injury while playing against the Celtics in Game 1 of the 2011 NBA Playoffs. The injury would keep Billups sidelined for the remainder of the playoffs.<ref>{{cite web|last=Prada|first=Mike|title=Chauncey Billups Could Miss Game 2 Of Celtics Vs. Knicks With Strained Knee|url=https://www.sbnation.com/nba/2011/4/17/2117267/chauncey-billups-injury-knicks-guard-strained-knee-in-celtics-series|work=Blog article|publisher=SB nation|accessdate=October 21, 2010}}</ref>\n\nShortly after the Knicks were eliminated from the playoffs by the [[2010\u201311 Boston Celtics season|Boston Celtics]], Billups mentioned he would love to return to the Knicks next season. \"I would love the opportunity to really try it up with these guys\", Billups said. \"Not like play 30 games after a trade, like really have a season. Have an opportunity to really get a fair shake with these guys. I would love to.\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Begley|first=Ian|title=Chauncey Billups: I want to come back|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/new-york/knicks/post/_/id/4805/chauncey-i-want-to-be-back-next-season|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=April 26, 2011}}</ref> In December 2011, the Knicks used their [[amnesty clause]] on Billups, and put him on waivers, ending his tenure with the Knicks.\n\n===Los Angeles Clippers (2011\u20132013)===\nAfter his tenure with the Knicks came to an end, Billups became an unrestricted free agent. Many believed that a contender like the [[2011\u201312 Miami Heat season|Miami Heat]] or the [[2011\u201312 Los Angeles Lakers season|Los Angeles Lakers]] would end up acquiring Billups. However, on December 12, 2011, the [[2011\u201312 Los Angeles Clippers season|Los Angeles Clippers]] claimed Billups off waivers. Billups indicated that he didn't want to be picked up by a team that was not contending for a championship and said he would retire if he was, pushing the NBA to warn him and his agent that he would be \"in breach of his contract\" if he did not show up.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/sports_blog/2011/12/the-clippers-have-won-the-winning-waiver-bid-on-chauncey-billups-who-was-amnestied-by-the-new-york-knicks-two-people-fami.html|work=Los Angeles Times|title=Clippers win waiver bid for Chauncey Billups|last=Turner|first=Broderick|date=December 11, 2011}}</ref> However, the Clippers ended up trading for the Hornets' superstar point guard [[Chris Paul]] two days later. After the Chris Paul trade, Billups said that he was happy to be with the Clippers, saying that \"I think these guys are ready to take the next leap and hopefully I can help with that.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/sports_blog/2011/12/chauncey-billups-ok-playing-for-clippers.html|title=Chauncey Billups OK with playing for Clippers|date=December 16, 2011|last=Turner|first=Broderick|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nBillups, a point guard, was moved into the [[shooting guard]] position, which he was still getting used to when he was injured.<ref name=\"comfort\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-clippers-fyi-20130310,0,441394.story|title=Clippers' Chauncey Billups still finding his comfort zone|first=Broderick|last=Turner|work=Los Angeles Times|date=March 9, 2013}}</ref> On February 7, 2012, an MRI revealed a tear in Billups's Achilles tendon, ending his season after only 20 game appearances.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/02/08/sports/basketball/nba-roundup.html | work=The New York Times | title=Clippers' Billups Has Torn Achilles', Ending His Season | date=February 7, 2012}}</ref> Billups helped the Clippers beat Miami, Oklahoma City, Orlando, and the Los Angeles Lakers en route to a 19\u20139 start.<ref>{{cite web|last=Broussard|first=Chris|title=Vinny Del Negro losing Clippers?|url=http://espn.go.com/los-angeles/nba/story/_/id/7723737/tension-high-los-angeles-clippers-players-vinny-del-negro-sources-say|publisher=ESPN The Magazine|accessdate=March 22, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn July 13, 2012, Billups re-signed with the Clippers on a 1-year deal. He made his season debut on November 28, 2012, against the [[2012\u201313 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Timberwolves]]. Billups was limited to only 22 games during the season because of various injuries,<ref name=\"teammate\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/sports/sportsnow/la-sp-sn-chauncey-billups-twyman-stokes-award-20130609,0,571180.story|title=Clippers' Chauncey Billups wins NBA's first 'best teammate' award|last=Bresnahan|first=Mike|work=Los Angeles Times|date=June 9, 2013}}</ref> including a sore back and tendinitis in his left foot.<ref name=\"comfort\" />\n\nOn June 10, 2013, Billups received the inaugural [[Twyman\u2013Stokes Teammate of the Year Award]]. Billups was humbled by the award, and said, \"For my name to be mentioned with <nowiki>[</nowiki>[[Jack Twyman]]<nowiki>]</nowiki>, I really don't feel worthy, to be honest with you. It's kind of embarrassing.\"<ref name=\"teammate\" /> During the 2012\u201313 season, Billups averaged a new career high free-throw percentage. He became a free agent after the season.\n\n===Return to Detroit Pistons (2013\u20132014)===\nOn July 16, 2013, Billups signed a two-year, $5 million contract to return to the [[2013\u201314 Detroit Pistons season|Detroit Pistons]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/2013/news/07/11/pistons-agree-with-billups.ap/|title=Billups agrees to return to Pistons with two-year deal|date=July 11, 2013|work=NBA.com|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc.|accessdate=July 14, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/pistons/news/pistons-sign-free-agent-guard-chauncey-billups|title=Pistons Sign Free Agent Guard Chauncey Billups|date=July 16, 2013|work=NBA.com|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc.|accessdate=July 16, 2013}}</ref> More knee problems caused him to miss most of the 2013\u201314 season, as he appeared in his fewest games since the [[1999\u20132000 NBA season|1999\u20132000 season]] and averaged career lows in points, minutes, steals, field goal percentage, and three-point percentage during the year. The Pistons finished the season at 29\u201353, and missed the postseason.\n\nOn June 30, 2014, the Pistons announced they would not pick up their [[NBA Salary Cap#Options|team option]] on Billups' contract for the 2014\u201315 season.<ref name=\"letgo\">{{cite news |url=http://www.nba.com/2014/news/06/30/pistons-chauncey-billups-06-230-2014.ap/index.html |title=Pistons not renewing Chauncey Billups' contract |work=NBA.com |date=June 30, 2014 |accessdate=June 30, 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn September 9, 2014, Billups announced his retirement from the NBA after 17 years.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2065864-chauncey-billups-retires-from-nba-after-17-year-career|title=Chauncey Billups Retires from NBA After 17-Year Career|first=Tim|last=Daniels|publisher=|accessdate=March 1, 2017}}</ref> Billups cited his health as the main reason for his retirement, as he never appeared in more than 22 games in his last three seasons in the league.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Billups says 'it's time' in announcing retirement|url = http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/11497483/chauncey-billups-says-retiring-17-nba-seasons|accessdate = April 1, 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn February 10, 2016, the Pistons retired Billups' No. 1 jersey.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/pistons/features/mr.-big-shot-slides-next-big-ben-pistons-honor-another-nbas-most-unique-champions |title=Mr. Big Shot slides in next to Big Ben as Pistons honor another of NBA's most unique champions |work=NBA.com |publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc. |first=Keith |last=Langlois |date=February 10, 2016 |accessdate=February 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==All-star appearances==\nIn 2006, Billups was selected to play in the [[2006 NBA All-Star Game]] as a reserve for the [[Eastern Conference (NBA)|Eastern Conference]], along with former teammates [[Richard Hamilton (basketball)|Richard Hamilton]], [[Rasheed Wallace]] and [[Ben Wallace]]. Pistons head coach [[Flip Saunders]] coached the Eastern Conference squad and put all four Pistons in the game when the east was falling behind; they were able to get the Eastern All-Star team back in the game. During the 2006 [[NBA All-Star Weekend]], Billups participated in the [[Three-point Shootout]] contest. He was eliminated in the first round of the contest after scoring 12 points. Billups called this moment when all four Pistons entered the game at the same time, one of the highlight moments of his career.\n\nIn the [[2007 NBA All-Star Game]], Billups was chosen as a reserve, along with teammate [[Richard Hamilton (basketball)|Richard Hamilton]], for the Eastern Conference, despite an injury that kept Billups out of five games early on in the season. Billups also took part in the [[Shooting Stars Competition]] alongside former Piston and [[Detroit Shock]] head coach [[Bill Laimbeer]] and Shock star [[Swin Cash]]. Team Detroit won the competition with Billups hitting the final half-court shot.<ref>{{cite web|title=NBA All-Star Shooting Stars Winners|date=August 24, 2017|website=NBA.com|url=http://www.nba.com/history/all-star/shooting-stars#/|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180224155543/http://www.nba.com/history/all-star/shooting-stars|archivedate=February 24, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBillups was selected to play as a reserve in the [[2008 NBA All-Star Game]], along with teammates Richard Hamilton and Rasheed Wallace, an injury replacement. Billups was the only Nugget to be selected to the [[2009 NBA All-Star Game]].\n\nBillups was chosen as the replacement by [[David Stern]] for injured [[New Orleans Hornets]] point guard [[Chris Paul]] at the [[2010 NBA All-Star Game]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nba.com/2010/allstar/2010/02/03/billups.replacement/index.html |publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc |work=NBA.com |title=Billups to replace Paul in 2010 NBA All-Star Game |date=February 3, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100206010922/http://www.nba.com/2010/allstar/2010/02/03/billups.replacement/index.html |archivedate=February 6, 2010 }}</ref>\n\n==BIG3==\n===Killer 3's (2017\u201319)===\nIn 2017, the creation of the 3-on-3 professional basketball league [[BIG3]] was announced, with Billups set to be a player for the Killer 3's.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://big3.com/index.php/news/123-new-team-chauncey-billups-stephen-jackson-unite-for-killer3s|title=NEW TEAM: Chauncey Billups & Stephen Jackson unite for KILLER3s|website=BIG3.com|access-date=February 15, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170516200356/http://big3.com/index.php/news/123-new-team-chauncey-billups-stephen-jackson-unite-for-killer3s|archive-date=May 16, 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==NBA career statistics==\n{{NBA player statistics legend|champion=y}}\n\n===Regular season===\n{{NBA player statistics start}}\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1997}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1997\u201398 Boston Celtics season|Boston]]\n| 51 || 44 || 25.4 || .390 || .339 || .817 || 2.2 || 4.3 || '''1.5''' || .0 || 11.1\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1997}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1997\u201398 Toronto Raptors season|Toronto]]\n| 29 || 26 || 31.7 || .349 || .316 || .919 || 2.7 || 3.3 || 1.0 || .1 || 11.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1998}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1998\u201399 Denver Nuggets season|Denver]]\n| 45 || 41 || 33.1 || .386 || .362 || .913 || 2.1 || 3.8 || 1.3 || .3 || 13.9\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|1999|trunc=y}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[1999\u20132000 Denver Nuggets season|Denver]]\n| 13 || 5 || 23.5 || .337 || .171 || .841 || 2.6 || 3.0 || .8 || .2 || 8.6\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2000}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2000\u201301 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Minnesota]]\n| 77 || 33 || 23.2 || .422 || .376 || .842 || 2.1 || 3.4 || .7 || .1 || 9.3\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| {{nbay|2001}}\n| style=\"text-align:left;\"| [[2001\u201302 Minnesota Timberwolves season|Minnesota]]\n| '''82''' || 54 || 28.7 || .423 || .394 || .885 || 2.8 || 5.5 || .8 || .2 || 12.5\n|-\n| s